{"title_page": "Majakka", "text_new": "{{Infobox building\n| name = '''Majakka'''\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| logo = \n| logo_size = \n| logo_alt = \n| logo_caption = \n| image = File:Majakka and Loisto, Kalasatama, Helsinki (July 2019, 3).jpg\n| image_size = \n| image_alt = <!-- or | alt = -->\n| image_caption = Ma\n| caption = Majakka under construction in July 2019\n| map_type            = Finland Helsinki (mainland)\n| map_alt             = \n| map_caption         = Location of Majakka within Helsinki\n| map_size = \n| map_dot_label = \n| map_dot_mark = \n| relief = \n| former_names = \n| alternate_names = \n| etymology = \n| status = Complete\n| cancelled = \n| topped_out = \n| building_type = Residential\n| architectural_style = \n| classification = \n| location = Kalasatama, [[Helsinki]], [[Finland]]\n| address = Kalasatamankatu 9A\n| location_city = \n| location_town = \n| location_country = \n| coordinates = {{coord|60|11|15.1|N|24|58|47.1|E|display=inline,title}}\n| altitude = \n| current_tenants = \n| namesake = \n| groundbreaking_date = \n| start_date = \n| stop_date = \n| topped_out_date = \n| completion_date = \n| opened_date = \n| inauguration_date = 25 November 2019\n| relocated_date = \n| renovation_date = \n| closing_date = \n| demolition_date = <!-- or | destruction_date    = -->\n| cost = \n| ren_cost = \n| client = \n| owner = {{ill|SRV-yhti\u00f6t|fi|lt=SRV}}\n| landlord = \n| affiliation = \n| height = \n| architectural = {{convert|134|m}}\n| tip = \n| antenna_spire = \n| roof = \n| top_floor = \n| observatory = \n| diameter = \n| circumference = \n| weight = \n| other_dimensions = \n| structural_system = \n| material = \n| size = \n| floor_count = 35\n| floor_area = \n| elevator_count = \n| grounds_area = \n| architect = Pekka Helin\n| architecture_firm = Arkkitehtitoimisto Pekka Helin & Co\n| developer = \n| engineer = \n| structural_engineer = \n| services_engineer = \n| civil_engineer = \n| other_designers = \n| quantity_surveyor = \n| main_contractor = {{ill|SRV-yhti\u00f6t|fi|lt=SRV}}\n| awards = \n| designations = \n| known_for = \n| ren_architect = \n| ren_firm = \n| ren_engineer = \n| ren_str_engineer = \n| ren_serv_engineer = \n| ren_civ_engineer = \n| ren_oth_designers = \n| ren_qty_surveyor = \n| ren_contractor = \n| ren_awards = \n| rooms = \n| unit_count = \n| parking = \n| website = {{URL|srv.fi/redi}}\n| embed = \n| embedded = \n| references = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Majakka''' ({{literal translation|[[lighthouse]]}}) is a high-rise building in [[Kalasatama]], [[Helsinki]]. It is the first [[skyscraper]]{{efn|When skyscraper is defined as exceeding 100 meters in height.}} in Finland and the second-tallest building in the [[Nordic countries]], after [[Turning Torso]] in [[Malm\u00f6]].\n\nThe tower is {{convert|134|m}} tall, making it the [[list of tallest buildings in Finland|tallest building in Finland]]. It is divided into 35 floors, and contains 283 residences.<ref>{{cite web |title=Suomen korkein asuintorni valmistuu parin vuoden p\u00e4\u00e4st\u00e4 \u2013 neli\u00f6hinnat vet\u00e4v\u00e4t hiljaiseksi |url=https://www.mtvuutiset.fi/artikkeli/suomen-korkein-asuintorni-valmistuu-parin-vuoden-paasta-neliohinnat-vetavat-hiljaiseksi/5680632#gs.x6oefg |website=mtvuutiset.fi |accessdate=17 February 2020}}</ref> The 5th floor has a garden open to the public. The tower is conjoined with the [[Redi (shopping centre)|Redi shopping centre]] and the [[Kalasatama metro station]]. The complex will include 7 other residential towers, as well as a hotel and offices, estimated to be completed in 2023.\n\nAfter delays related to [[water damage]], the first tenants moved in on November 25th, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.talouselama.fi/uutiset/rakentaminen-myohastyi-vesivahinko-vaurioitti-srvn-35-kerroksinen-tornitalo-on-viimein-muuttovalmis-ja-talta-se-nyt-nayttaa/a558fb96-a7a9-4af6-9d5d-628541f15d66|title=Rakentaminen my\u00f6h\u00e4styi, vesivahinko vaurioitti \u2013 SRV:n 35-kerroksinen tornitalo on viimein muuttovalmis, ja t\u00e4lt\u00e4 se nyt n\u00e4ytt\u00e4\u00e4|first=Mirva|last=Heiskanen|website=[[Talousel\u00e4m\u00e4]]|access-date=2019-11-28|lang=fi}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Helsinki]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures under construction in Finland]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox building\n| name = '''Majakka'''\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| logo = \n| logo_size = \n| logo_alt = \n| logo_caption = \n| image = File:Majakka and Loisto, Kalasatama, Helsinki (July 2019, 3).jpg\n| image_size = \n| image_alt = <!-- or | alt = -->\n| image_caption = Ma\n| caption = Majakka under construction in July 2019\n| map_type            = Finland Helsinki (mainland)\n| map_alt             = \n| map_caption         = Location of Majakka within Helsinki\n| map_size = \n| map_dot_label = \n| map_dot_mark = \n| relief = \n| former_names = \n| alternate_names = \n| etymology = \n| status = Complete\n| cancelled = \n| topped_out = \n| building_type = Residential\n| architectural_style = \n| classification = \n| location = Kalasatama, [[Helsinki]], [[Finland]]\n| address = Kalasatamankatu 9A\n| location_city = \n| location_town = \n| location_country = \n| coordinates = {{coord|60|11|15.1|N|24|58|47.1|E|display=inline,title}}\n| altitude = \n| current_tenants = \n| namesake = \n| groundbreaking_date = \n| start_date = \n| stop_date = \n| topped_out_date = \n| completion_date = \n| opened_date = \n| inauguration_date = 25 November 2019\n| relocated_date = \n| renovation_date = \n| closing_date = \n| demolition_date = <!-- or | destruction_date    = -->\n| cost = \n| ren_cost = \n| client = \n| owner = {{ill|SRV-yhti\u00f6t|fi|lt=SRV}}\n| landlord = \n| affiliation = \n| height = \n| architectural = {{convert|134|m}}\n| tip = \n| antenna_spire = \n| roof = \n| top_floor = \n| observatory = \n| diameter = \n| circumference = \n| weight = \n| other_dimensions = \n| structural_system = \n| material = \n| size = \n| floor_count = 35\n| floor_area = \n| elevator_count = \n| grounds_area = \n| architect = Pekka Helin\n| architecture_firm = Arkkitehtitoimisto Pekka Helin & Co\n| developer = \n| engineer = \n| structural_engineer = \n| services_engineer = \n| civil_engineer = \n| other_designers = \n| quantity_surveyor = \n| main_contractor = {{ill|SRV-yhti\u00f6t|fi|lt=SRV}}\n| awards = \n| designations = \n| known_for = \n| ren_architect = \n| ren_firm = \n| ren_engineer = \n| ren_str_engineer = \n| ren_serv_engineer = \n| ren_civ_engineer = \n| ren_oth_designers = \n| ren_qty_surveyor = \n| ren_contractor = \n| ren_awards = \n| rooms = \n| unit_count = \n| parking = \n| website = {{URL|srv.fi/redi}}\n| embed = \n| embedded = \n| references = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Majakka''' ({{literal translation|[[lighthouse]]}}) is a high-rise building in [[Kalasatama]], [[Helsinki]]. It is the first [[skyscraper]]{{efn|When skyscraper is defined as exceeding 100 meters in height.}} in Finland and the second-tallest in the [[Nordic countries]], after [[Turning Torso]] in [[Malm\u00f6]].\n\nThe tower is {{convert|134|m}} tall, making it the [[list of tallest buildings in Finland|tallest building in Finland]]. It is divided into 35 floors, and contains 283 residences.<ref>{{cite web |title=Suomen korkein asuintorni valmistuu parin vuoden p\u00e4\u00e4st\u00e4 \u2013 neli\u00f6hinnat vet\u00e4v\u00e4t hiljaiseksi |url=https://www.mtvuutiset.fi/artikkeli/suomen-korkein-asuintorni-valmistuu-parin-vuoden-paasta-neliohinnat-vetavat-hiljaiseksi/5680632#gs.x6oefg |website=mtvuutiset.fi |accessdate=17 February 2020}}</ref> The 5th floor has a garden open to the public. The tower is conjoined with the [[Redi (shopping centre)|Redi shopping centre]] and the [[Kalasatama metro station]]. The complex will include 7 other residential towers, as well as a hotel and offices, estimated to be completed in 2023.\n\nAfter delays related to [[water damage]], the first tenants moved in on November 25th, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.talouselama.fi/uutiset/rakentaminen-myohastyi-vesivahinko-vaurioitti-srvn-35-kerroksinen-tornitalo-on-viimein-muuttovalmis-ja-talta-se-nyt-nayttaa/a558fb96-a7a9-4af6-9d5d-628541f15d66|title=Rakentaminen my\u00f6h\u00e4styi, vesivahinko vaurioitti \u2013 SRV:n 35-kerroksinen tornitalo on viimein muuttovalmis, ja t\u00e4lt\u00e4 se nyt n\u00e4ytt\u00e4\u00e4|first=Mirva|last=Heiskanen|website=[[Talousel\u00e4m\u00e4]]|access-date=2019-11-28|lang=fi}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Helsinki]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures under construction in Finland]]\n", "name_user": "Jonik", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Majakka"}
{"title_page": "Abdelkrim Rais", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Abdelkrim Rais<br/>\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0631\u064a\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0627\u064a\u0633\n| background       = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| caption          = \n| landscape        = \n| alt              = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = \n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = [[1912]]\n| birth_place      = [[Fez]], [[Morocco]]\n| death_date       = 30 August [[1996]]\n| death_place      = [[Fez]], [[Morocco]]\n| genre            = [[Andalusian classical music|Andalusian Music]]\n| occupation       = \n| instrument       = [[Rubab (instrument)|Rabab]]\n| years_active     = 1945 - 1996\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = \n}}\n'''Abdelkrim Rais''' ([[Fez]] 1912 \u2013 October 31, 1998) (in [[Arabic language|Arabic]]: '''\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0631\u064a\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0627\u064a\u0633''') was a [[Morocco|Moroccan]] writer and musician of traditional [[Andalusian classical music|Andalusian Music]]. Known as the ''captain of al-Ala (Andalusian music)'', he was also a [[Rebab]] (spiked fiddle) [[virtuoso]]<ref>[https://www.allmusic.com/artist/abdelkrim-rais-mn0000586656 Abdelkrim  Rais - AllMusic.]</ref>.\n\n== Life ==\nAbdelkrim Rais was born in [[1912]] in the old town of [[Fez]] in [[Morocco]]. He was encouraged by his family to engage in [[Andalusian classical music|Andalusian Music]] and started learning at the musical conservatory of his hometown, while working in his father's printing press, one of the first in Morocco<ref>[http://maarifpress.com/news6627.html Abdelkrim Rais - The captain of Andalusian Music - Maarif Press (2014).]</ref>.\n\nIn [[1946]], and after the death of his master [[Mohammed Al Brihi]], he took over the leadership of the Arabo-Andalus Orchestra of Fez<ref>[https://fesfestival.com/2019/en/evenement/lart-du-muwashhah-dalep-a-fes/ L\u2019ART DU MUWASHAH D\u2019ALEP A FEZ (2019).]</ref>. The Orchestra was dedicated to the preservation, transmission and authentic interpretation of [[Andalusian classical music|Arabo-Andalusian music]]; a repertoire which originated at the end of the [[Reconquista]] period (15-16th centuries), when Muslims and Jews were expelled from Spain<ref>[https://www.bozar.be/en/activities/140962-mohamed-briouel-l-orchestre-arabo-andalou-de-fes MOHAMED BRIOUEL & L'ORCHESTRE ARABO-ANDALOU DE F\u00c8S - Morocco (2019).]</ref>.\n\nIn [[1969]], Abdelkim Rais became the director of the Academy of Music of Fez, and remained the city's Orchestra lead until his death in [[1996]] at the age of 84. The orchestra has continued since then under the direction of Mohamed Briouel.\n\n==Books==\nIn parallel with his musical career, Abdelkrim Rais published several writings that had a major influence on the evolution of contemporary Moroccan Andalusian music. Those include:\n* Booklet - Introduction to the bases of [[Andalusian classical music|Andalusian Music]] ([[1970]]), used by the ministry of culture in [[Morocco]].\n* Inspirations from [[Mohammed al-Haik|Al-Haik]] Songbook Poems ([[1982]]).\n* Collection and documentation of all [[Andalusi nubah|Andalusi nubas]], co-written with Mohamed Briouel ([[1986]]).\n==See also==\n*[[Mohamed Bajeddoub]]\n*[[Mohammed al-Haik]]\n\n== Footnotes ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:1996 deaths]]\n[[Category:Moroccan folk singers]]\n[[Category:Moroccan male singers]]\n[[Category:People from Fez, Morocco]]\n[[Category:20th-century singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century male singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Abdelkrim Rais<br/>\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0631\u064a\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0627\u064a\u0633\n| background       = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| caption          = \n| landscape        = \n| alt              = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = \n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = [[1912]]\n| birth_place      = [[Fez]], [[Morocco]]\n| death_date       = 30 August [[1996]]\n| death_place      = [[Fez]], [[Morocco]]\n| genre            = [[Andalusian classical music|Andalusian Music]]\n| occupation       = \n| instrument       = [[Rabab]]\n| years_active     = 1945 - 1996\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = \n}}\n'''Abdelkrim Rais''' ([[Fez]] 1912 \u2013 October 31, 1998) (in [[Arabic language|Arabic]]: '''\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0631\u064a\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0627\u064a\u0633''') was a [[Morocco|Moroccan]] writer and musician of traditional [[Andalusian classical music|Andalusian Music]]. Known as the ''captain of al-Ala (Andalusian music)'', he was also a [[Rebab]] (spiked fiddle) [[virtuoso]]<ref>[https://www.allmusic.com/artist/abdelkrim-rais-mn0000586656 Abdelkrim  Rais - AllMusic.]</ref>.\n\n== Life ==\nAbdelkrim Rais was born in [[1912]] in the old town of [[Fez]] in [[Morocco]]. He was encouraged by his family to engage in [[Andalusian classical music|Andalusian Music]] and started learning at the musical conservatory of his hometown, while working in his father's printing press, one of the first in Morocco<ref>[http://maarifpress.com/news6627.html Abdelkrim Rais - The captain of Andalusian Music - Maarif Press (2014).]</ref>.\n\nIn [[1946]], and after the death of his master [[Mohammed Al Brihi]], he took over the leadership of the Arabo-Andalus Orchestra of Fez<ref>[https://fesfestival.com/2019/en/evenement/lart-du-muwashhah-dalep-a-fes/ L\u2019ART DU MUWASHAH D\u2019ALEP A FEZ (2019).]</ref>. The Orchestra was dedicated to the preservation, transmission and authentic interpretation of [[Andalusian classical music|Arabo-Andalusian music]]; a repertoire which originated at the end of the [[Reconquista]] period (15-16th centuries), when Muslims and Jews were expelled from Spain<ref>[https://www.bozar.be/en/activities/140962-mohamed-briouel-l-orchestre-arabo-andalou-de-fes MOHAMED BRIOUEL & L'ORCHESTRE ARABO-ANDALOU DE F\u00c8S - Morocco (2019).]</ref>.\n\nIn [[1969]], Abdelkim Rais became the director of the Academy of Music of Fez, and remained the city's Orchestra lead until his death in [[1996]] at the age of 84. The orchestra has continued since then under the direction of Mohamed Briouel.\n\n==Books==\nIn parallel with his musical career, Abdelkrim Rais published several writings that had a major influence on the evolution of contemporary Moroccan Andalusian music. Those include:\n* Booklet - Introduction to the bases of [[Andalusian classical music|Andalusian Music]] ([[1970]]), used by the ministry of culture in [[Morocco]].\n* Inspirations from [[Mohammed al-Haik|Al-Haik]] Songbook Poems ([[1982]]).\n* Collection and documentation of all [[Andalusi nubah|Andalusi nubas]], co-written with Mohamed Briouel ([[1986]]).\n==See also==\n*[[Mohamed Bajeddoub]]\n*[[Mohammed al-Haik]]\n\n== Footnotes ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:1996 deaths]]\n[[Category:Moroccan folk singers]]\n[[Category:Moroccan male singers]]\n[[Category:People from Fez, Morocco]]\n[[Category:20th-century singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century male singers]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toRabab(link changed toRubab (instrument)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abdelkrim_Rais"}
{"title_page": "Traditional Techniques", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Traditional Techniques\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Stephen Malkmus]]\n| cover      = Cover of Traditional Techniques by Stephen Malkmus.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|2020|03|06}}\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = *[[Folk rock]]\n*[[psychedelic rock]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=41|s=5}}\n| label      =\n*[[Matador Records|Matador]]\n*[[Domino Recording Company|Domino]]\n| producer   = [[Chris Funk]]\n| prev_title = [[Groove Denied]]\n| prev_year  = 2019\n| year       = 2020\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n'''''Traditional Techniques''''' is the third studio album by American musician [[Stephen Malkmus]]. It was released on March 6, 2020 by [[Matador Records]] and [[Domino Recording Company]].<ref name=\"rs_news\">{{cite web |last1=Shaffer |first1=Claire |title=Stephen Malkmus Announces New Album 'Traditional Techniques', Shares 'Xian Man' |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/stephen-malkmus-traditional-techniques-xian-man-940897/ |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=6 March 2020|date=2020-01-22 }}</ref><ref name=\"NMEannounce\">{{cite web |last1=Moore |first1=Sam |title=Listen to Stephen Malkmus' 'Xian Man' from his new album 'Traditional Techniques' |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/stephen-malkmus-traditional-techniques-new-album-xian-man-2599916 |website=[[NME]] |accessdate=6 March 2020|date=2020-01-22 }}</ref>\n\n==Background and recording==\n\nMalkmus conceived the idea for ''Traditional Techniques'' during the recording of ''[[Sparkle Hard]]''.<ref name=\"tq_news\">{{cite web |last1=Eede |first1=Christian |title=Stephen Malkmus Announces New Album |url=https://thequietus.com/articles/27713-stephen-malkmus-new-album-traditional-techniques |website=[[The Quietus]] |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref> According to a press release, the concept gained traction and became a fully realized album in a matter of weeks.<ref name=\"cos_news\">{{cite web |last1=Schatz |first1=Lake |title=Stephen Malkmus announces new album Traditional Techniques, plots North American tour |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/01/stephen-malkmus-traditional-techniques-tour-dates-tickets/ |website=[[Consequence of Sound]] |accessdate=6 March 2020|date=2020-01-22 }}</ref> Recording of the album took place in [[Portland, Oregon]], at Halfling Studio. The album was produced by [[Chris Funk]] of [[The Decemberists]] and features guitarist [[Matt Sweeney]] and musician [[Qais Essar]].<ref name=\"pitchfork\"/>\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n|MC = 81/100<ref name=\"mc\">{{cite web |title=Traditional Techniques by Stephen Malkmus Reviews and Tracks |url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/traditional-techniques/stephen-malkmus |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n|ADM = 7.5/10<ref name=\"adm\">{{cite web |title=Traditional Techniques by Stephen Malkmus reviews |url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/review/11293/Stephen-Malkmus-Traditional-Techniques.aspx |website=[[AnyDecentMusic?]] |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n|rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"am\">{{AllMusic | class= album | id= mw0003350797| title= Review of ''Traditional Techniques'' | first= Stephen Thomas | last= Erlewine | accessdate= March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n|rev2 = ''[[American Songwriter]]''\n|rev2score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"as\">{{cite web |last1=Chris |first1=Rutledge |title=Stephen Malkmus Drops New Phase of Folk on 'Traditional Techniques' |url=https://americansongwriter.com/stephen-malkmus-traditional-techniques-album-review/chris-rutledge/ |website=[[American Songwriter]] |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n|rev3 = ''[[DIY (magazine)|DIY]]''\n|rev3score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"diy\">{{cite web |last1=Doherty |first1=Jack |title=Stephen Malkmus - Traditional Techniques |url=https://diymag.com/2020/03/05/stephen-malkmus-traditional-techniques-album-review |website=[[DIY (magazine)|DIY]] |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n|rev4 = ''[[Loud and Quiet]]''\n|rev4score = 8/10<ref name=\"LnQ\">{{cite web |last1=Walton |first1=Sam |title=Stephen Malkmus - Traditional Techniques - Album Review |url=https://www.loudandquiet.com/reviews/stephen-malkmus-traditional-techniques/ |website=[[Loud and Quiet]] |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n|rev5 = ''[[NME]]''\n|rev5score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"NMEreview\">{{cite web |last1=Rigotti |first1=Alex |title=Stephen Malkmus \u2013 'Traditional Techniques' review: folky experimentalism and dad jokes galore |url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/stephen-malkmus-traditional-techniques-review-2621707 |website=[[NME]] |accessdate=6 March 2020|date=2020-03-06 }}</ref>\n|rev6 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n|rev6score = 7.7/10<ref name=\"pitchfork\">{{cite web |last1=Rytlewski |first1=Evan |title=Stephen Malkmus: Traditional Techniques Album Review |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/stephen-malkmus-traditional-techniques/ |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n|rev7 = ''[[PopMatters]]''\n|rev7score = {{Rating|7|10}}<ref name=\"pm\">{{cite web |last1=Cochrun |first1=Kyle |title=Stephen Malkmus Goes Folk on 'Traditional Techniques' |url=https://www.popmatters.com/stephen-malkmus-traditional-techniques-2645370434.html |website=[[PopMatters]] |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n|rev8 = ''[[The Skinny (magazine)|The Skinny]]''\n|rev8score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"skinny\">{{cite web |last1=Wade |first1=Lewis |title=Stephen Malkmus \u2013 Traditional Techniques |url=https://www.theskinny.co.uk/music/reviews/albums/stephen-malkmus-traditional-techniques |website=[[The Skinny (magazine)|The Skinny]] |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n|rev9 = ''[[Slant Magazine]]''\n|rev9score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"slant\">{{cite web |last1=Rowin |first1=Michael Joshua |title=Review: Stephen Malkmus's Traditional Techniques Challenges Form and Function |url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review-stephen-malkmus-traditional-techniques-challenges-form-and-function/ |website=[[Slant Magazine]] |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n|rev10 = ''[[Spectrum Culture]]''\n|rev10score = {{Rating|3.25|5}}<ref name=\"spectrum\">{{cite web |last1=Hazelwood |first1=Holly |title=Stephen Malkmus: Traditional Techniques |url=https://spectrumculture.com/2020/03/05/stephen-malkmus-traditional-techniques-review/ |website=[[Spectrum Culture]] |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n''Traditional Techniques'' received positive reviews from music critics. Many critics praised Malkmus' foray into [[folk music]]. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[Standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream publications, the album received an [[Weighted arithmetic mean|average]] score of 81, based on fourteen reviews, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref name=\"mc\"/>\n\nWriting for ''[[Loud and Quiet]]'', Sam Walton gave the album a positive review, praising it as \"an expertly written and performed exploration of muted psych-rock and various strands of folk music\".<ref name=\"LnQ\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| total_length  = 41:05\n| all_writing   = [[Stephen Malkmus]]\n| title1        = A.C.C. Kirtan\n| length1       = 6:20\n| title2        = Xian Man\n| length2       = 4:06\n| title3        = The Greatest Own in Legal History\n| length3       = 3:48\n| title4        = Cash Up\n| length4       = 4:06\n| title5        = Shadowbanned\n| length5       = 3:23\n| title6        = What Kind of Person\n| length6       = 3:28\n| title7        = Flowin' Robes\n| length7       = 2:52\n| title8        = Brainwashed\n| length8       = 5:00\n| title9        = Signal Western\n| length9       = 3:46\n| title10       = Amberjack\n| length10      = 4:16\n}}\n\n==Credits==\n\nAdapted from [[Allmusic]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/traditional-techniques-mw0003350797/credits|title=Stephen Malkmus Traditional Techniques|accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref>:\n{{div col}}\n*[[Stephen Malkmus]] - composer, lead vocals, guitar, bass\n*[[Chris Funk]] - [[autoharp]], [[dobro]], Moog synthesizer, pedal steel, [[weissenborn]], producer\n*[[Blake Mills]] - guitar\n*Bill Athens - bass\n*[[Qais Essar]] - [[Rubab (instrument)|rabab]]\n*Eric Zang - [[daf]], [[kaval]], [[udu]]\n*[[Matt Sweeney]] - electric guitar, acoustic guitar, vocals\n*[[Spooner Oldham]] - wurlitzer\n*Joy Pearson - vocals\n*Dan Hunt - drums, percussion\n{{div col end}}\n===Additional credits===\n{{div col}}\n*Sharmila Banerjee - illustrations\n*Jan Lankisch - design\n*Adam Lee - mixing\n*Jeff Lipton - mastering\n*Maria Rice - mastering\n*Jason Quigley - photography\n{{div col end}}\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2020 albums]]\n[[Category:Stephen Malkmus albums]]\n[[Category:Matador Records albums]]\n[[Category:Domino Recording Company albums]]\n{{Authority control}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Traditional Techniques\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Stephen Malkmus]]\n| cover      = Cover of Traditional Techniques by Stephen Malkmus.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|2020|03|06}}\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = *[[Folk rock]]\n*[[psychedelic rock]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=41|s=5}}\n| label      =\n*[[Matador Records|Matador]]\n*[[Domino Recording Company|Domino]]\n| producer   = [[Chris Funk]]\n| prev_title = [[Groove Denied]]\n| prev_year  = 2019\n| year       = 2020\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n'''''Traditional Techniques''''' is the third studio album by American musician [[Stephen Malkmus]]. It was released on March 6, 2020 by [[Matador Records]] and [[Domino Recording Company]].<ref name=\"rs_news\">{{cite web |last1=Shaffer |first1=Claire |title=Stephen Malkmus Announces New Album 'Traditional Techniques', Shares 'Xian Man' |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/stephen-malkmus-traditional-techniques-xian-man-940897/ |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=6 March 2020|date=2020-01-22 }}</ref><ref name=\"NMEannounce\">{{cite web |last1=Moore |first1=Sam |title=Listen to Stephen Malkmus' 'Xian Man' from his new album 'Traditional Techniques' |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/stephen-malkmus-traditional-techniques-new-album-xian-man-2599916 |website=[[NME]] |accessdate=6 March 2020|date=2020-01-22 }}</ref>\n\n==Background and recording==\n\nMalkmus conceived the idea for ''Traditional Techniques'' during the recording of ''[[Sparkle Hard]]''.<ref name=\"tq_news\">{{cite web |last1=Eede |first1=Christian |title=Stephen Malkmus Announces New Album |url=https://thequietus.com/articles/27713-stephen-malkmus-new-album-traditional-techniques |website=[[The Quietus]] |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref> According to a press release, the concept gained traction and became a fully realized album in a matter of weeks.<ref name=\"cos_news\">{{cite web |last1=Schatz |first1=Lake |title=Stephen Malkmus announces new album Traditional Techniques, plots North American tour |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/01/stephen-malkmus-traditional-techniques-tour-dates-tickets/ |website=[[Consequence of Sound]] |accessdate=6 March 2020|date=2020-01-22 }}</ref> Recording of the album took place in [[Portland, Oregon]], at Halfling Studio. The album was produced by [[Chris Funk]] of [[The Decemberists]] and features guitarist [[Matt Sweeney]] and musician [[Qais Essar]].<ref name=\"pitchfork\"/>\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n|MC = 81/100<ref name=\"mc\">{{cite web |title=Traditional Techniques by Stephen Malkmus Reviews and Tracks |url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/traditional-techniques/stephen-malkmus |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n|ADM = 7.5/10<ref name=\"adm\">{{cite web |title=Traditional Techniques by Stephen Malkmus reviews |url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/review/11293/Stephen-Malkmus-Traditional-Techniques.aspx |website=[[AnyDecentMusic?]] |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n|rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"am\">{{AllMusic | class= album | id= mw0003350797| title= Review of ''Traditional Techniques'' | first= Stephen Thomas | last= Erlewine | accessdate= March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n|rev2 = ''[[American Songwriter]]''\n|rev2score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"as\">{{cite web |last1=Chris |first1=Rutledge |title=Stephen Malkmus Drops New Phase of Folk on 'Traditional Techniques' |url=https://americansongwriter.com/stephen-malkmus-traditional-techniques-album-review/chris-rutledge/ |website=[[American Songwriter]] |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n|rev3 = ''[[DIY (magazine)|DIY]]''\n|rev3score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"diy\">{{cite web |last1=Doherty |first1=Jack |title=Stephen Malkmus - Traditional Techniques |url=https://diymag.com/2020/03/05/stephen-malkmus-traditional-techniques-album-review |website=[[DIY (magazine)|DIY]] |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n|rev4 = ''[[Loud and Quiet]]''\n|rev4score = 8/10<ref name=\"LnQ\">{{cite web |last1=Walton |first1=Sam |title=Stephen Malkmus - Traditional Techniques - Album Review |url=https://www.loudandquiet.com/reviews/stephen-malkmus-traditional-techniques/ |website=[[Loud and Quiet]] |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n|rev5 = ''[[NME]]''\n|rev5score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"NMEreview\">{{cite web |last1=Rigotti |first1=Alex |title=Stephen Malkmus \u2013 'Traditional Techniques' review: folky experimentalism and dad jokes galore |url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/stephen-malkmus-traditional-techniques-review-2621707 |website=[[NME]] |accessdate=6 March 2020|date=2020-03-06 }}</ref>\n|rev6 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n|rev6score = 7.7/10<ref name=\"pitchfork\">{{cite web |last1=Rytlewski |first1=Evan |title=Stephen Malkmus: Traditional Techniques Album Review |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/stephen-malkmus-traditional-techniques/ |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n|rev7 = ''[[PopMatters]]''\n|rev7score = {{Rating|7|10}}<ref name=\"pm\">{{cite web |last1=Cochrun |first1=Kyle |title=Stephen Malkmus Goes Folk on 'Traditional Techniques' |url=https://www.popmatters.com/stephen-malkmus-traditional-techniques-2645370434.html |website=[[PopMatters]] |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n|rev8 = ''[[The Skinny (magazine)|The Skinny]]''\n|rev8score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"skinny\">{{cite web |last1=Wade |first1=Lewis |title=Stephen Malkmus \u2013 Traditional Techniques |url=https://www.theskinny.co.uk/music/reviews/albums/stephen-malkmus-traditional-techniques |website=[[The Skinny (magazine)|The Skinny]] |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n|rev9 = ''[[Slant Magazine]]''\n|rev9score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"slant\">{{cite web |last1=Rowin |first1=Michael Joshua |title=Review: Stephen Malkmus's Traditional Techniques Challenges Form and Function |url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review-stephen-malkmus-traditional-techniques-challenges-form-and-function/ |website=[[Slant Magazine]] |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n|rev10 = ''[[Spectrum Culture]]''\n|rev10score = {{Rating|3.25|5}}<ref name=\"spectrum\">{{cite web |last1=Hazelwood |first1=Holly |title=Stephen Malkmus: Traditional Techniques |url=https://spectrumculture.com/2020/03/05/stephen-malkmus-traditional-techniques-review/ |website=[[Spectrum Culture]] |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n''Traditional Techniques'' received positive reviews from music critics. Many critics praised Malkmus' foray into [[folk music]]. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[Standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream publications, the album received an [[Weighted arithmetic mean|average]] score of 81, based on fourteen reviews, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref name=\"mc\"/>\n\nWriting for ''[[Loud and Quiet]]'', Sam Walton gave the album a positive review, praising it as \"an expertly written and performed exploration of muted psych-rock and various strands of folk music\".<ref name=\"LnQ\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| total_length  = 41:05\n| all_writing   = [[Stephen Malkmus]]\n| title1        = A.C.C. Kirtan\n| length1       = 6:20\n| title2        = Xian Man\n| length2       = 4:06\n| title3        = The Greatest Own in Legal History\n| length3       = 3:48\n| title4        = Cash Up\n| length4       = 4:06\n| title5        = Shadowbanned\n| length5       = 3:23\n| title6        = What Kind of Person\n| length6       = 3:28\n| title7        = Flowin' Robes\n| length7       = 2:52\n| title8        = Brainwashed\n| length8       = 5:00\n| title9        = Signal Western\n| length9       = 3:46\n| title10       = Amberjack\n| length10      = 4:16\n}}\n\n==Credits==\n\nAdapted from [[Allmusic]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/traditional-techniques-mw0003350797/credits|title=Stephen Malkmus Traditional Techniques|accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref>:\n{{div col}}\n*[[Stephen Malkmus]] - composer, lead vocals, guitar, bass\n*[[Chris Funk]] - [[autoharp]], [[dobro]], Moog synthesizer, pedal steel, [[weissenborn]], producer\n*[[Blake Mills]] - guitar\n*Bill Athens - bass\n*[[Qais Essar]] - [[rabab]]\n*Eric Zang - [[daf]], [[kaval]], [[udu]]\n*[[Matt Sweeney]] - electric guitar, acoustic guitar, vocals\n*[[Spooner Oldham]] - wurlitzer\n*Joy Pearson - vocals\n*Dan Hunt - drums, percussion\n{{div col end}}\n===Additional credits===\n{{div col}}\n*Sharmila Banerjee - illustrations\n*Jan Lankisch - design\n*Adam Lee - mixing\n*Jeff Lipton - mastering\n*Maria Rice - mastering\n*Jason Quigley - photography\n{{div col end}}\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2020 albums]]\n[[Category:Stephen Malkmus albums]]\n[[Category:Matador Records albums]]\n[[Category:Domino Recording Company albums]]\n{{Authority control}}\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toRabab(link changed toRubab (instrument)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Traditional_Techniques"}
{"title_page": "Moira Rayner", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer\n| name = Moira Rayner\n| image = Moira Rayner, Australian barrister and human rights advocate.jpg\n| birth_name = Moira Emilie Stockwell\n| birth_date = November 10, 1948\n| birth_place = New Zealand\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| residence = East [[Melbourne]], Victoria, Australia\n| alma_mater = [[University of Western Australia]]\n\n| genre = Public Policy, Social Justice\n| notableworks = | \nspouse =\n| partner = \n| children = \n| signature =\n| website = www.moirarayner.com.au\n| module = \n|embed  = \n|title =\n|filename = \n|type = \n|description = }}\n\n'''Moira Emilie Rayner''' (n\u00e9e '''Stockwell''', born November 10 1948), is a New Zealand-born, Australian-based barrister and human rights advocate.<ref name=\"who\">{{cite book|last1=Rayner|first1=Moira|title=Who's who in Australia 2008 : an Australian biographical dictionary and register of prominent people, with which is incorporated Johns's notable Australians (first issued 1906)|date=2008|publisher=Crown Content|isbn=1740951603|edition=44th|location=North Melbourne, Vic, Australia|page=1765}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.womenaustralia.info/lawyers/biogs/AWE5662b.htm|title=Rayner, Moira - Biographical entry - Australian Women Lawyers as Active Citizens|last=Melbourne|first=The University of|website=www.womenaustralia.info|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> She was the first Commissioner for Equal Opportunity appointed by the Victorian Government under the Equal Opportunity Act 1984, an office which she held until 1994. In this position she was responsible for monitoring the Equal Opportunity Act; the [[Racial Discrimination Act 1975]], the Human Rights and Equal Opportunity Commission Act 1986, and the Commonwealth legislated Sex Discrimination Act 1984.Simultaneously, in 1986, she was appointed a Commissioner of the [[Law Reform Commission of Western Australia]] a position she held until 1990.\nIn 2000 Rayner became the first Director of the office of Childrens\u2019 Rights Commissioner for the city of London, UK.<ref name=breekveldt>{{cite book |last1=Breekveldt |first1=Norah |title=Career interrupted : how 14 successful women navigate career breaks |date=2018 |publisher=Melbourne Books |location=Melbourne, Vic, Australia |pages=26-35|isbn=1922129879 }}</ref><ref name=register>{{cite web |last1=National Foundation for Australian Women |title=Rayner, Moira |url=https://www.womenaustralia.info/biogs/AWE5662b.htm |website=The Australian Women's Register |publisher=University of Melbourne |accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nin 1994 the Australian Federal government appointed her to the Institute of Family Studies to undertake a special project to fight child abuse.<ref name=crowley>{{cite web |last1=Crowley |first1=Rosemary |title=Senator |url=https://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/download/media/pressrel/O0P10/upload_binary/O0P10.pdf;fileType=application%2Fpdf#search=%22media/pressrel/O0P10%22 |website=Parliament of Australia information |publisher=Minister for Family Services |accessdate=21 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nRayner used her time in her official positions, and as an author and activist, to address issues and support campaigns for the rights of women in society and the rights of children in the legal system. Many of her activities in these spheres have been innovative and thus publicly and politically controversial.<ref>{{cite web |title=How Kennett Gets Away With it |page=urban planning agenda para.9 |url=https://www.greenleft.org.au/content/how-kennett-gets-away-it |publisher=The Green left |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Rayner |first1=Moira |title=Nice guys of Victoria politics finish last |url=https://www.eurekastreet.com.au/article/nice-guys-of-victorian-politics-finish-last |website=Eureka Street |publisher=Eureka Street |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nRayner is a great granddaughter of the New Zealand politician and Minister for Native Affairs, [[John Bryce]]. She was born in [[Dunedin]], New Zealand into an observant Protestant family, the second of three children. She completed her primary and secondary education at [[Columba College]], Dunedin, and at the age of sixteen her family moved to Western Australia, where she began her study of law.<ref name=register/><ref name=breekveldt/>\n\nHaving graduated with honours in law from the [[University of Western Australia]], Rayner was admitted to the Bar in 1972 and, at age 27, established her own legal firm. She also practised as a solicitor advocate in Perth from 1975. As a barrister she joined the Independent Western Australian Bar Association in 1985.<ref name=who/>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1986 she was appointed a Commissioner of the [[Law Reform Commission of Western Australia]] a position she held until 1990.<ref name=register/><ref name=who/> In 1987 she completed a [[Winston Churchill Memorial Trusts|Churchill Fellowship]] on the rights of children in the legal system of the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"register\" /><ref name=\"who\" /> In 1988 she was elected Chairman of the ''Law Reform Commission of Western Australia''.<ref name=\"who\" /><ref name=\"register\" />\n\nFrom 1990 until 1994 Rayner held the office of [[Victorian Equal Opportunity and Human Rights Commission|Victorian Commissioner for Equal Opportunity]] in Victoria, the body responsible for monitoring the application of the ''Equal Opportunity Act 1984''; [[Racial Discrimination Act 1975]], and the ''Human Rights and Equal Opportunity Commission Act 1986''., and the Commonwealth legislated ''Sex Discrimination Act 1984\u2019'.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sex Discrimination Act 1984 |url=https://www.legislation.gov.au/Details/C2014C00002 |website=Federal Register of Legislation (Australia) |publisher=Australian Government |accessdate=9 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Human Rights and Equal Opportunity Commission Act 1986|url=https://www.legislation.gov.au/Details/C2006C00094 |website=Federal Register of Legislation (Australia) |publisher=Australian Government |accessdate=9 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=How Victoria's Equal Opportunity Act has changed over time |url=https://www.humanrightscommission.vic.gov.au/home/the-law/equal-opportunity-act/timeline-of-victoria-s-equal-opportunity-law |website=Human Rights Commission of Victoria |publisher=Victorian Equal Opportunity and Human Rights Commission |accessdate=9 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn a 1994 dispute with the newly elected government led by Jeff Kennett regarding Rayner\u2019s stance against the closure of women\u2019s prisons in Victoria, the Act was amended and the office of Commissioner was abolished.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Merritt |first1=Chris |title=Hulls puts ex-staffer on board |url=https://www.news.com.au/news/hulls-puts-ex-staffer-on-board/news-story/505d64c2fdbf74ee48eb3c3e2aad04aa |website=News |publisher=News.com.au |accessdate=12 April 2020 |pages=paras 13 and 16}}</ref> Later in 1994 the Australian Federal government appointed her to the Institute of Family Studies to undertake a special project to fight child abuse.<ref name=\"crowley\" />\n\nRayner then joined the national law firm ''Dunhill Madden Butler'' (later ''Norton Rose Fulbright'') where she practised industrial, workplace relations and discrimination law for seven years (1994-2001).<ref>{{cite web |title=Lawyers Weekly - Appointments |url=https://www.lawyersweekly.com.au/appointments/16507-justitia-mp-appointed-to-supreme-court |website=Lawyers Weekly |publisher=Momentum Media |accessdate=October 10, 2019}}</ref>\nUntil 2000 Rayner chaired both the Financial Planning Association's independent Dispute Resolution Scheme, and the Board of Directors of the [[Child Rights Taskforce \u2013 Australia|National Children's and Youth Law Centre Inc]].<ref name=register/><ref name=spirit>{{cite web |last1=Kohn |first1=Rachael |title=The Spirit of Things, My Spiritual Diary: Moira Rayner, from Osho to Iggy |url=https://www.abc.net.au/radionational/programs/spiritofthings/my-spiritual-diary3a-moira-rayner/4091152?searchTerm=Moira+Rayner#transcript |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Commission |accessdate=20 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, Rayner moved to London to work with the Lord Mayor of the Greater London Authority, as the founding Director of the independently funded Office of the Children's Rights Commissioner for London implementing provisions of  United Nations [[Convention on the Rights of the Child]] (2003).<ref>{{cite web |title=Children's Rights Commissioner |url=https://www.childrenscommissioner.gov.uk |website=Children's Commissioner |publisher=United Kingdom Government |accessdate=22 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nRayner resigned as Acting Commissioner of the [[Corruption and Crime Commission]] of Western Australia amid an accusation of corruption of which she was later acquitted. She had warned a dying friend that he should be careful what he said on the phone as authorities could be listening. The jury judged it to be a \"slip of the tongue\", made in a moment of distress without criminal intent. In reply to a question by ABC journalist [[Rachael Kohn]], Rayner described the incident.\n<blockquote>''I was (falsely) accused of acting with the corrupt intention of perverting the course of justice, by visiting a long-term friend of mine who was dying in a hospice. He had been found to have been stealing from the parliament and to have been using drugs, which were totally out of character.''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/the-price-of-friendship-20051029-ge14zz.html|title=The Price of Friendship|website=theage.com.au|publisher=The Age -(Fairfax)-Melbourne|accessdate=4 February 2020|ref=29 October, 2005}}</ref><ref name=spirit/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news.com.au/national/ex-commissioner-cleared-over-phone-tap-warning/news-story/0d9b65fa60469c0f366327fc005a420c|title=Ex-commissioner cleared over phone tap warning|last1=Perpitch|first1=Nicholas|website=News.com.au|publisher=AAP|accessdate=23 August 2019|ref=17 March 2009}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nOther appointments have included\n\n*[[University of Melbourne]] (Advisory Board Labour Law Centre; Senior Fellow),\n*[[Deakin University]]  (Adjunct Professor, Centre for Human Services),\n*[[RMIT University]] (Adjunct Professor, School of Social Inquiry);\n*[[Murdoch University]] (Visiting Scholar),\n*[[University of Western Australia]] (Lecturer, Senior Fellow Law School, Visiting Fellow at the Australian Centre)\n*[[Curtin University]] (Lecturer)\n*[[Australian Institute of Family Studies]] (Deputy Director, Research).<ref name=\"register\" /><ref name=\"spirit\" />\n\nFor the last fifteen years Rayner has been a prolific commentator in the online current affairs periodical ''[[New Matilda]]''. Articles include analyses of animal rights, indigenous policy, human rights, funeral celebrancy and the ''[[Australian Competition and Consumer Commission]]'', the [[Timeline of the 2005 London bombings|London bombing]] attacks, and [[Michael Jackson]]\u2019s victims. \n<ref>https://newmatilda.com/?s=Moira+Rayner</ref> In ''[[Eureka Street (magazine)|Eureka Street]]'' she wrote defending Victorian Police Commissioner [[Christine Nixon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/the-price-of-friendship-20051029-ge14zz.html|title=The crucifixion of Christine Nixon|last1=Rayner|first1=Moira|website=eurekastreet.com.au|publisher=Eureka Street|accessdate=4 February 2020|ref=9 April, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Spiritual Journey==\nRayner was raised in a very observant Presbyterian family in which she claims to have been influenced to believe in high ideals of justice and fairness.\nLater on she explored various forms of religious belief. She was particularly influenced by the early spiritual teaching of Bhagwan Shree Rajneesh (later known as 'Osho') known as the [[Rajneesh movement|Orange People]] and their deep focus on meditation.\nShe spent time in the Rajneesh community in Pune, India and in Oregon in the USA . \nIn recent years she has become deeply influenced by and a practitioner and giver of the Spiritual Exercises of Saint [[Ignatius of Loyola]] and became a member of the teaching team at the Campion Centre of Ignatian Spirituality in Kew, Victoria.<ref name=\"spirit\" />\n\n==Published Works==\n[[File:Joan kirner.jpg|thumb|upright|right|[[Joan Kirner]], first female Premier of Victoria, Australia, from 1990 to 1992]]\n'''''Rooting Democracy: Growing the Society We Want'''''\n(with Jenny Lee)\n\n<blockquote>''The book explains that democracy can only flourish with visible accountable government. Of particular importance are the safeguards for the less visible - and thus more vulnerable - institutions, such as public prosecutors, human rights commissions, the independence of the judiciary and public service, Freedom of Information (FOI), ombudsmen and other \"watchdogs\" which provide the checks and balances vital to democracy.''<ref>{{cite book |last1=Rayner |first1=Moira |title=Rooting Democracy: Growing the Society We Want |date=1997 |publisher=Allen and Unwin |isbn=1864481323}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n'''The Women's Power Handbook'''\n(with [[Joan Kirner]], former Premier of Victoria.\n<blockquote> ''The content consists of advice to those women who would be community activists, politicians or senior executives. It advises one how to attain power and use it to advantage society.''\n''Inter alia, it describes how to forge alliances with like-minded women, how to discuss tactics for managing meetings, and how to use the media''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Rayner |first1=Moira |title=The Women's Power Handbook |date=1999 |publisher=Viking Australia |location=Melbourne |isbn=0670887773}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Szego |first1=Julie |title=Life on Mars |url=https://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/books/life-on-mars-20050604-ge0a6h.html |website=there.com.au |publisher=The Age, Melbourne, Victoria |accessdate=20 June 2019}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n<br />\n== External Links==       \nRachael Kohn interviews Moira Rayner on [https://www.abc.net.au/radionational/programs/spiritofthings/my-spiritual-diary3a-moira-rayner/4091152?searchTerm=Moira+Rayner#transcript/  the ABC's ''Spirit of Things'']\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rayner, Moira}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Australian barristers]]\n\n[[Category:Writers from Melbourne]]\n\n[[Category:People from Dunedin]]\n[[Category:Australian women lawyers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Australian women activists]]\n[[Category:Australian feminist writers]]\n[[Category:Australian spiritual writers]]\n[[Category:Australian human rights activists]]\n[[Category:Australian women academics]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Zealand emigrants to Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer\n| name = Moira Rayner\n| image = Moira Rayner, Australian barrister and human rights advocate.jpg\n| birth_name = Moira Emilie Stockwell\n| birth_date = November 10, 1948\n| birth_place = New Zealand\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| residence = East [[Melbourne]], Victoria, Australia\n| alma_mater = [[University of Western Australia]]\n\n| genre = Public Policy, Social Justice\n| notableworks = | \nspouse =\n| partner = \n| children = \n| signature =\n| website = www.moirarayner.com.au\n| module = \n|embed  = \n|title =\n|filename = \n|type = \n|description = }}\n\n'''Moira Emilie Rayner''' (n\u00e9e '''Stockwell''', born November 10 1948), is a New Zealand-born, Australian-based barrister and human rights advocate.<ref name=\"who\">{{cite book|last1=Rayner|first1=Moira|title=Who's who in Australia 2008 : an Australian biographical dictionary and register of prominent people, with which is incorporated Johns's notable Australians (first issued 1906)|date=2008|publisher=Crown Content|isbn=1740951603|edition=44th|location=North Melbourne, Vic, Australia|page=1765}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.womenaustralia.info/lawyers/biogs/AWE5662b.htm|title=Rayner, Moira - Biographical entry - Australian Women Lawyers as Active Citizens|last=Melbourne|first=The University of|website=www.womenaustralia.info|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> She was the first Commissioner for Equal Opportunity appointed by the Victorian Government under the Equal Opportunity Act 1984, an office which she held until 1994. In this position she was responsible for monitoring the Equal Opportunity Act; the [[Racial Discrimination Act 1975]], the Human Rights and Equal Opportunity Commission Act 1986, and the Commonwealth legislated Sex Discrimination Act 1984.Simultaneously, in 1986, she was appointed a Commissioner of the [[Law Reform Commission of Western Australia]] a position she held until 1990.\nIn 2000 Rayner became the first Director of the office of Childrens\u2019 Rights Commissioner for the city of London, UK.<ref name=breekveldt>{{cite book |last1=Breekveldt |first1=Norah |title=Career interrupted : how 14 successful women navigate career breaks |date=2018 |publisher=Melbourne Books |location=Melbourne, Vic, Australia |pages=26-35|isbn=1922129879 }}</ref><ref name=register>{{cite web |last1=National Foundation for Australian Women |title=Rayner, Moira |url=https://www.womenaustralia.info/biogs/AWE5662b.htm |website=The Australian Women's Register |publisher=University of Melbourne |accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nin 1994 the Australian Federal government appointed her to the Institute of Family Studies to undertake a special project to fight child abuse.<ref name=crowley>{{cite web |last1=Crowley |first1=Rosemary |title=Senator |url=https://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/download/media/pressrel/O0P10/upload_binary/O0P10.pdf;fileType=application%2Fpdf#search=%22media/pressrel/O0P10%22 |website=Parliament of Australia information |publisher=Minister for Family Services |accessdate=21 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nRayner used her time in her official positions, and as an author and activist, to address issues and support campaigns for the rights of women in society and the rights of children in the legal system. Many of her activities in these spheres have been innovative and thus publicly and politically controversial.<ref>{{cite web |title=How Kennett Gets Away With it |page=urban planning agenda para.9 |url=https://www.greenleft.org.au/content/how-kennett-gets-away-it |publisher=The Green left |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Rayner |first1=Moira |title=Nice guys of Victoria politics finish last |url=https://www.eurekastreet.com.au/article/nice-guys-of-victorian-politics-finish-last |website=Eureka Street |publisher=Eureka Street |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nRayner is a great granddaughter of the New Zealand politician and Minister for Native Affairs, [[John Bryce]]. She was born in [[Dunedin]], New Zealand into an observant Protestant family, the second of three children. She completed her primary and secondary education at [[Columba College]], Dunedin, and at the age of sixteen her family moved to Western Australia, where she began her study of law.<ref name=register/><ref name=breekveldt/>\n\nHaving graduated with honours in law from the [[University of Western Australia]], Rayner was admitted to the Bar in 1972 and, at age 27, established her own legal firm. She also practised as a solicitor advocate in Perth from 1975. As a barrister she joined the Independent Western Australian Bar Association in 1985.<ref name=who/>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1986 she was appointed a Commissioner of the [[Law Reform Commission of Western Australia]] a position she held until 1990.<ref name=register/><ref name=who/> In 1987 she completed a [[Winston Churchill Memorial Trusts|Churchill Fellowship]] on the rights of children in the legal system of the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"register\" /><ref name=\"who\" /> In 1988 she was elected Chairman of the ''Law Reform Commission of Western Australia''.<ref name=\"who\" /><ref name=\"register\" />\n\nFrom 1990 until 1994 Rayner held the office of [[Victorian Equal Opportunity and Human Rights Commission|Victorian Commissioner for Equal Opportunity]] in Victoria, the body responsible for monitoring the application of the ''Equal Opportunity Act 1984''; [[Racial Discrimination Act 1975]], and the ''Human Rights and Equal Opportunity Commission Act 1986''., and the Commonwealth legislated ''Sex Discrimination Act 1984\u2019'.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sex Discrimination Act 1984 |url=https://www.legislation.gov.au/Details/C2014C00002 |website=Federal Register of Legislation (Australia) |publisher=Australian Government |accessdate=9 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Human Rights and Equal Opportunity Commission Act 1986|url=https://www.legislation.gov.au/Details/C2006C00094 |website=Federal Register of Legislation (Australia) |publisher=Australian Government |accessdate=9 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=How Victoria's Equal Opportunity Act has changed over time |url=https://www.humanrightscommission.vic.gov.au/home/the-law/equal-opportunity-act/timeline-of-victoria-s-equal-opportunity-law |website=Human Rights Commission of Victoria |publisher=Victorian Equal Opportunity and Human Rights Commission |accessdate=9 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn a 1994 dispute with the newly elected government led by Jeff Kennett regarding Rayner\u2019s stance against the closure of women\u2019s prisons in Victoria, the Act was amended and the office of Commissioner was abolished.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Merritt |first1=Chris |title=Hulls puts ex-staffer on board |url=https://www.news.com.au/news/hulls-puts-ex-staffer-on-board/news-story/505d64c2fdbf74ee48eb3c3e2aad04aa |website=News |publisher=News.com.au |accessdate=12 April 2020 |pages=paras 13 and 16}}</ref> Later in 1994 the Australian Federal government appointed her to the Institute of Family Studies to undertake a special project to fight child abuse.<ref name=\"crowley\" />\n\nRayner then joined the national law firm ''Dunhill Madden Butler'' (later ''Norton Rose Fulbright'') where she practised industrial, workplace relations and and discrimination law for seven years (1994-2001).<ref>{{cite web |title=Lawyers Weekly - Appointments |url=https://www.lawyersweekly.com.au/appointments/16507-justitia-mp-appointed-to-supreme-court |website=Lawyers Weekly |publisher=Momentum Media |accessdate=October 10, 2019}}</ref>\nUntil 2000 Rayner chaired both the Financial Planning Association's independent Dispute Resolution Scheme, and the Board of Directors of the [[Child Rights Taskforce \u2013 Australia|National Children's and Youth Law Centre Inc]].<ref name=register/><ref name=spirit>{{cite web |last1=Kohn |first1=Rachael |title=The Spirit of Things, My Spiritual Diary: Moira Rayner, from Osho to Iggy |url=https://www.abc.net.au/radionational/programs/spiritofthings/my-spiritual-diary3a-moira-rayner/4091152?searchTerm=Moira+Rayner#transcript |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Commission |accessdate=20 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, Rayner moved to London to work with the Lord Mayor of the Greater London Authority, as the founding Director of the independently funded Office of the Children's Rights Commissioner for London implementing provisions of  United Nations [[Convention on the Rights of the Child]] (2003).<ref>{{cite web |title=Children's Rights Commissioner |url=https://www.childrenscommissioner.gov.uk |website=Children's Commissioner |publisher=United Kingdom Government |accessdate=22 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nRayner resigned as Acting Commissioner of the [[Corruption and Crime Commission]] of Western Australia amid an accusation of corruption of which she was later acquitted. She had warned a dying friend that he should be careful what he said on the phone as authorities could be listening. The jury judged it to be a \"slip of the tongue\", made in a moment of distress without criminal intent. In reply to a question by ABC journalist [[Rachael Kohn]], Rayner described the incident.\n<blockquote>''I was (falsely) accused of acting with the corrupt intention of perverting the course of justice, by visiting a long-term friend of mine who was dying in a hospice. He had been found to have been stealing from the parliament and to have been using drugs, which were totally out of character.''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/the-price-of-friendship-20051029-ge14zz.html|title=The Price of Friendship|website=theage.com.au|publisher=The Age -(Fairfax)-Melbourne|accessdate=4 February 2020|ref=29 October, 2005}}</ref><ref name=spirit/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news.com.au/national/ex-commissioner-cleared-over-phone-tap-warning/news-story/0d9b65fa60469c0f366327fc005a420c|title=Ex-commissioner cleared over phone tap warning|last1=Perpitch|first1=Nicholas|website=News.com.au|publisher=AAP|accessdate=23 August 2019|ref=17 March 2009}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nOther appointments have included\n\n*[[University of Melbourne]] (Advisory Board Labour Law Centre; Senior Fellow),\n*[[Deakin University]]  (Adjunct Professor, Centre for Human Services),\n*[[RMIT University]] (Adjunct Professor, School of Social Inquiry);\n*[[Murdoch University]] (Visiting Scholar),\n*[[University of Western Australia]] (Lecturer, Senior Fellow Law School, Visiting Fellow at the Australian Centre)\n*[[Curtin University]] (Lecturer)\n*[[Australian Institute of Family Studies]] (Deputy Director, Research).<ref name=\"register\" /><ref name=\"spirit\" />\n\nFor the last fifteen years Rayner has been a prolific commentator in the online current affairs periodical ''[[New Matilda]]''. Articles include analyses of animal rights, indigenous policy, human rights, funeral celebrancy and the ''[[Australian Competition and Consumer Commission]]'', the [[Timeline of the 2005 London bombings|London bombing]] attacks, and [[Michael Jackson]]\u2019s victims. \n<ref>https://newmatilda.com/?s=Moira+Rayner</ref> In ''[[Eureka Street (magazine)|Eureka Street]]'' she wrote defending Victorian Police Commissioner [[Christine Nixon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/the-price-of-friendship-20051029-ge14zz.html|title=The crucifixion of Christine Nixon|last1=Rayner|first1=Moira|website=eurekastreet.com.au|publisher=Eureka Street|accessdate=4 February 2020|ref=9 April, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Spiritual Journey==\nRayner was raised in a very observant Presbyterian family in which she claims to have been influenced to believe in high ideals of justice and fairness.\nLater on she explored various forms of religious belief. She was particularly influenced by the early spiritual teaching of Bhagwan Shree Rajneesh (later known as 'Osho') known as the [[Rajneesh movement|Orange People]] and their deep focus on meditation.\nShe spent time in the Rajneesh community in Pune, India and in Oregon in the USA . \nIn recent years she has become deeply influenced by and a practitioner and giver of the Spiritual Exercises of Saint [[Ignatius of Loyola]] and became a member of the teaching team at the Campion Centre of Ignatian Spirituality in Kew, Victoria.<ref name=\"spirit\" />\n\n==Published Works==\n[[File:Joan kirner.jpg|thumb|upright|right|[[Joan Kirner]], first female Premier of Victoria, Australia, from 1990 to 1992]]\n'''''Rooting Democracy: Growing the Society We Want'''''\n(with Jenny Lee)\n\n<blockquote>''The book explains that democracy can only flourish with visible accountable government. Of particular importance are the safeguards for the less visible - and thus more vulnerable - institutions, such as public prosecutors, human rights commissions, the independence of the judiciary and public service, Freedom of Information (FOI), ombudsmen and other \"watchdogs\" which provide the checks and balances vital to democracy.''<ref>{{cite book |last1=Rayner |first1=Moira |title=Rooting Democracy: Growing the Society We Want |date=1997 |publisher=Allen and Unwin |isbn=1864481323}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n'''The Women's Power Handbook'''\n(with [[Joan Kirner]], former Premier of Victoria.\n<blockquote> ''The content consists of advice to those women who would be community activists, politicians or senior executives. It advises one how to attain power and use it to advantage society.''\n''Inter alia, it describes how to forge alliances with like-minded women, how to discuss tactics for managing meetings, and how to use the media''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Rayner |first1=Moira |title=The Women's Power Handbook |date=1999 |publisher=Viking Australia |location=Melbourne |isbn=0670887773}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Szego |first1=Julie |title=Life on Mars |url=https://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/books/life-on-mars-20050604-ge0a6h.html |website=there.com.au |publisher=The Age, Melbourne, Victoria |accessdate=20 June 2019}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n<br />\n== External Links==       \nRachael Kohn interviews Moira Rayner on [https://www.abc.net.au/radionational/programs/spiritofthings/my-spiritual-diary3a-moira-rayner/4091152?searchTerm=Moira+Rayner#transcript/  the ABC's ''Spirit of Things'']\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rayner, Moira}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Australian barristers]]\n\n[[Category:Writers from Melbourne]]\n\n[[Category:People from Dunedin]]\n[[Category:Australian women lawyers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Australian women activists]]\n[[Category:Australian feminist writers]]\n[[Category:Australian spiritual writers]]\n[[Category:Australian human rights activists]]\n[[Category:Australian women academics]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Zealand emigrants to Australia]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moira_Rayner"}
{"title_page": "Josh Martinez", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{About|the Canadian musician|the ''[[Big Brother 19 (U.S.)]]'' contestant|Josh Martinez (television personality)}}\n{{Infobox musical artist| <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Josh Martinez\n| image               = Josh_Martinez.jpg\n| caption             = Josh Martinez performing in 2005\n| image_size          =\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Matthew Edward Kimber\n| birth_place         =\n| birth_date          = August 6, 1977\n| death_date          =\n| origin              =\n| instrument          =\n| genre               = [[Alternative hip hop]]<br>[[Indie hip hop]]\n| occupation          = [[Rapper]], singer\n| years_active        =\n| label               = Camobear Records<br/>[[Bella Union]]\n| associated_acts     = [[The Chicharones]]<br>The Pissed Off Wild\n| website             = http://www.joshmartinez.ca\n| current_members     =\n| past_members        =\n}}\n\n'''Matthew Edward Kimber''' (born August 6, 1977), better known by his stage name '''Josh Martinez''', is a Canadian [[rapper]],<ref name=Mercury>{{cite web|url=http://www.portlandmercury.com/portland/Content?oid=753222&category=22153 |title=The Holy Trinity |last=Barey |first=Graham |date=April 7, 2008 |work=Portland Mercury |accessdate=August 19, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5s6fhptws?url=http://www.portlandmercury.com/portland/Content?oid=753222&category=22153 |archivedate=August 19, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> record producer and record label executive. In the early 2000s, Martinez started his own label, Camobear Records,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straight.com/article/martinez-prepares-for-war |title=Martinez Prepares for War |last=Turenne |first=Martin |date=January 29, 2009 |work=[[The Georgia Straight]] |accessdate=August 19, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5s6g0UsOH?url=http://www.straight.com/article/martinez-prepares-for-war |archivedate=August 19, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> to which fellow rap artist [[Moka Only]] is signed. Josh Martinez was once named by [[Urb Magazine]] as one of its \"Next 100 Rising Stars\".{{Citation needed|date=August 2010}}\n\n==Biography==\nIn addition to pursuing a solo career, Josh is a founding member of both the [[Chicharones]] and the Pissed Off Wild. The Chicharones is an underground pop and hip hop project in collaboration with rapper [[Sleep (rapper)|Sleep]] of Oldominion,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boiseweekly.com/boise/all-you-can-eat/Content?oid=1013598 |title=All-You-Can-Eat |last=Atkins |first=Amy |date=December 17, 2008 |work=Boise Weekly |accessdate=August 19, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5s6gCDSjU?url=http://www.boiseweekly.com/boise/all-you-can-eat/Content?oid=1013598 |archivedate=August 19, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> following a chance meeting between the two at [[South By Southwest]] that led to the eventual formation of the group.<ref name=\"Coleman\" /> The Pissed Off Wild, (or the P.O.W.), is a live rock band which Martinez fronts.<ref name=\"Coleman\">{{cite web|url=http://www.spinner.ca/2010/03/16/josh-martinez-interview-sxsw-2010/ |title=Josh Martinez Interview: SXSW 2010 |last=Coleman |first=Denzil |date=March 16, 2010 |work=Spinner Canada |accessdate=August 19, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5s6gkiUEn?url=http://www.spinner.ca/2010/03/16/josh-martinez-interview-sxsw-2010/ |archivedate=August 19, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Musically the band draws from artists such as [[333 Foreign]] and [[Beck]].\n\nMartinez' 2005 solo album, ''Midriff Music'', produced by Southern California DJ Samix won the \"Best Rap Recording\" award at the 2005 [[Western Canadian Music Awards]]. After the success of his many solo albums and Chicharones material, he proceeded to work on material for his follow-up solo album, ''World Famous Sex Buffet''. Working with some of his regular production partners, he also enlisted the help of some notable guests artists whom he had met over the years. These include [[Devin The Dude]], [[Classified (rapper)|Classified]], [[Pigeon John]], indie rock band [[Mother Mother]], Sleep and [[Awol One]]. Touring the world, Martinez has shared the stage and road with acts such as [[Sage Francis]], [[Sole (artist)|Sole]] and [[Alias (artist)|Alias]] of [[Anticon]].\n\nMartinez currently resides in [[Portland, Oregon]].<ref name=\"Mercury\" />\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n* ''The Cracker'' (1998) <small>(with Crackbeat Society)</small>\n* ''Josh Martinez & the Hooded Fang'' (1999)\n* ''Made in China'' (2000)\n* ''Buck Up Princess'' (2003)\n* ''[[Midriff Music]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[When Pigs Fly (The Chicharones album)|When Pigs Fly]]'' (2005) <small>(with [[Sleep (rapper)|Sleep]], as [[The Chicharones]])</small>\n* ''Splitsville'' (2007) <small>(with DJ Moves & [[Awol One]])</small>\n* ''The World Famous Sex Buffet'' (2008)\n* ''Pissed Off Wild'' (2011)\n* ''Swine Flew'' (2012) <small>(with Sleep, as The Chicharones)</small>\n* ''Blotto'' (2013)\n\n===EPs===\n* ''Maximum Wellbeing'' (1998)\n* ''Rumble Pie'' (2002)\n* ''The Good Life'' (2002)\n* ''Boss Hogs EP'' (2003) <small>(with Sleep, as The Chicharones)</small>\n* ''Pork Rind Disco EP'' (2005) <small>(with Sleep, as The Chicharones)</small>\n* ''Skullduggery'' (2008)\n* ''Swine Country'' (2009) <small>(with Sleep, as The Chicharones)</small>\n\n===Mixtapes===\n* ''Por Que? (Pork Eh?)'' (2012) <small>(with Sleep, as The Chicharones)</small>\n\n===Compilations===\n* ''Low Pressure The Compilation'' <small>(with DJ Moves) (2001)</small>\n* ''A Trash Up'' (2006)\n* ''Toke City Special'' (2010) <small>(with Sleep, as The Chicharones)</small>\n\n===Live===\n* ''On and Cracklin''' (2006) <small>(with Sleep, as The Chicharones)</small>\n* ''Live in Bozeman, MT'' (2009) <small>(with Sleep, as The Chicharones)</small>\n\n===Singles===\n* ''Offbeats 7\" Series Vol. 1'' (2002) <small>(with Omid)</small>\n* ''Hard Fall'' (2004)\n* ''Nightmares Remix'' (2005)\n\n===Appears on===\n* [[Factor (producer)|Factor]] \u2013 \"The Leen\" from ''Chandelier'' (2008)\n* [[Noah23]] \u2013 \"Moon Landing\" from ''[[Rock Paper Scissors (album)|Rock Paper Scissors]]'' (2008)\n* Factor \u2013 \"PopStravaganza\" from ''[[Lawson Graham]]'' (2010)\n* Factor \u2013 \"Where I'm at Now\" from ''Old Souls Vol. 2'' (2010)\n*\" Drive Thru\" from Raise the Bridges \"Beauty in the Trenches\"(2011)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.joshmartinez.ca Josh Martinez]\n* [http://www.myspace.com/thejoshmartinez Josh Martinez MySpace]\n* [http://www.chicharones.com/ The Chicharones]\n* [http://camobeardigital.com/ Camobear Records]\n* [http://www.cbcradio3.com/issues/2005_01_28/index.cfm?page=43 Haligonian Poesy in Effect: The Tumbling Verse of Josh Martinez]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120309155623/http://breakoutwest.ca/awards/previous-years/2005-awards/ Breakout West \u2013 2005 Awards]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Martinez, Josh}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Canadian male rappers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian rappers]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Oregon]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n[[Category:Bella Union artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian rappers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{About|the Canadian musician|the ''[[Big Brother 19 (U.S.)]]'' contestant|Josh Martinez (television personality)}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist| <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Josh Martinez\n| image               = Josh_Martinez.jpg\n| caption             = Josh Martinez performing in 2005\n| image_size          =\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Matthew Edward Kimber\n| birth_place         =\n| birth_date          = August 6, 1977\n| death_date          =\n| origin              =\n| instrument          =\n| genre               = [[Alternative hip hop]]<br>[[Indie hip hop]]\n| occupation          = [[Rapper]], singer\n| years_active        =\n| label               = Camobear Records<br/>[[Bella Union]]\n| associated_acts     = [[The Chicharones]]<br>The Pissed Off Wild\n| website             = http://www.joshmartinez.ca\n| current_members     =\n| past_members        =\n}}\n'''Matthew Edward Kimber''' (born August 6, 1977), better known by his stage name '''Josh Martinez''', is a Canadian [[rapper]],<ref name=Mercury>{{cite web|url=http://www.portlandmercury.com/portland/Content?oid=753222&category=22153 |title=The Holy Trinity |last=Barey |first=Graham |date=April 7, 2008 |work=Portland Mercury |accessdate=August 19, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5s6fhptws?url=http://www.portlandmercury.com/portland/Content?oid=753222&category=22153 |archivedate=August 19, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> record producer and record label executive. In the early 2000s, Martinez started his own label, Camobear Records,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straight.com/article/martinez-prepares-for-war |title=Martinez Prepares for War |last=Turenne |first=Martin |date=January 29, 2009 |work=[[The Georgia Straight]] |accessdate=August 19, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5s6g0UsOH?url=http://www.straight.com/article/martinez-prepares-for-war |archivedate=August 19, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> to which fellow rap artist [[Moka Only]] is signed. Josh Martinez was once named by [[Urb Magazine]] as one of its \"Next 100 Rising Stars\".{{Citation needed|date=August 2010}}\n\n==Biography==\nIn addition to pursuing a solo career, Josh is a founding member of both the [[Chicharones]] and the Pissed Off Wild. The Chicharones is an underground pop and hip hop project in collaboration with rapper [[Sleep (rapper)|Sleep]] of Oldominion,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boiseweekly.com/boise/all-you-can-eat/Content?oid=1013598 |title=All-You-Can-Eat |last=Atkins |first=Amy |date=December 17, 2008 |work=Boise Weekly |accessdate=August 19, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5s6gCDSjU?url=http://www.boiseweekly.com/boise/all-you-can-eat/Content?oid=1013598 |archivedate=August 19, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> following a chance meeting between the two at [[South By Southwest]] that led to the eventual formation of the group.<ref name=\"Coleman\" /> The Pissed Off Wild, (or the P.O.W.), is a live rock band which Martinez fronts.<ref name=\"Coleman\">{{cite web|url=http://www.spinner.ca/2010/03/16/josh-martinez-interview-sxsw-2010/ |title=Josh Martinez Interview: SXSW 2010 |last=Coleman |first=Denzil |date=March 16, 2010 |work=Spinner Canada |accessdate=August 19, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5s6gkiUEn?url=http://www.spinner.ca/2010/03/16/josh-martinez-interview-sxsw-2010/ |archivedate=August 19, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Musically the band draws from artists such as [[333 Foreign]] and [[Beck]].\n\nMartinez' 2005 solo album, ''Midriff Music'', produced by Southern California DJ Samix won the \"Best Rap Recording\" award at the 2005 [[Western Canadian Music Awards]]. After the success of his many solo albums and Chicharones material, he proceeded to work on material for his follow-up solo album, ''World Famous Sex Buffet''. Working with some of his regular production partners, he also enlisted the help of some notable guests artists whom he had met over the years. These include [[Devin The Dude]], [[Classified (rapper)|Classified]], [[Pigeon John]], indie rock band [[Mother Mother]], Sleep and [[Awol One]]. Touring the world, Martinez has shared the stage and road with acts such as [[Sage Francis]], [[Sole (artist)|Sole]] and [[Alias (artist)|Alias]] of [[Anticon]].\n\nMartinez currently resides in [[Portland, Oregon]].<ref name=\"Mercury\" />\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n* ''The Cracker'' (1998) <small>(with Crackbeat Society)</small>\n* ''Josh Martinez & the Hooded Fang'' (1999)\n* ''Made in China'' (2000)\n* ''Buck Up Princess'' (2003)\n* ''[[Midriff Music]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[When Pigs Fly (The Chicharones album)|When Pigs Fly]]'' (2005) <small>(with [[Sleep (rapper)|Sleep]], as [[The Chicharones]])</small>\n* ''Splitsville'' (2007) <small>(with DJ Moves & [[Awol One]])</small>\n* ''The World Famous Sex Buffet'' (2008)\n* ''Pissed Off Wild'' (2011)\n* ''Swine Flew'' (2012) <small>(with Sleep, as The Chicharones)</small>\n* ''Blotto'' (2013)\n\n===EPs===\n* ''Maximum Wellbeing'' (1998)\n* ''Rumble Pie'' (2002)\n* ''The Good Life'' (2002)\n* ''Boss Hogs EP'' (2003) <small>(with Sleep, as The Chicharones)</small>\n* ''Pork Rind Disco EP'' (2005) <small>(with Sleep, as The Chicharones)</small>\n* ''Skullduggery'' (2008)\n* ''Swine Country'' (2009) <small>(with Sleep, as The Chicharones)</small>\n\n===Mixtapes===\n* ''Por Que? (Pork Eh?)'' (2012) <small>(with Sleep, as The Chicharones)</small>\n\n===Compilations===\n* ''Low Pressure The Compilation'' <small>(with DJ Moves) (2001)</small>\n* ''A Trash Up'' (2006)\n* ''Toke City Special'' (2010) <small>(with Sleep, as The Chicharones)\n\n===Live===\n* ''On and Cracklin''' (2006) <small>(with Sleep, as The Chicharones)</small>\n* ''Live in Bozeman, MT'' (2009) <small>(with Sleep, as The Chicharones)</small>\n\n===Singles===\n* ''Offbeats 7\" Series Vol. 1'' (2002) <small>(with Omid)</small>\n* ''Hard Fall'' (2004)\n* ''Nightmares Remix'' (2005)\n\n===Appears on===\n* [[Factor (producer)|Factor]] \u2013 \"The Leen\" from ''Chandelier'' (2008)\n* [[Noah23]] \u2013 \"Moon Landing\" from ''[[Rock Paper Scissors (album)|Rock Paper Scissors]]'' (2008)\n* Factor \u2013 \"PopStravaganza\" from ''[[Lawson Graham]]'' (2010)\n* Factor \u2013 \"Where I'm at Now\" from ''Old Souls Vol. 2'' (2010)\n*\" Drive Thru\" from Raise the Bridges \"Beauty in the Trenches\"(2011)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.joshmartinez.ca Josh Martinez]\n* [http://www.myspace.com/thejoshmartinez Josh Martinez MySpace]\n* [http://www.chicharones.com/ The Chicharones]\n* [http://camobeardigital.com/ Camobear Records]\n* [http://www.cbcradio3.com/issues/2005_01_28/index.cfm?page=43 Haligonian Poesy in Effect: The Tumbling Verse of Josh Martinez]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120309155623/http://breakoutwest.ca/awards/previous-years/2005-awards/ Breakout West \u2013 2005 Awards]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Martinez, Josh}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Canadian male rappers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian rappers]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Oregon]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n[[Category:Bella Union artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian rappers]]\n", "name_user": "Derek R Bullamore", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Josh_Martinez"}
{"title_page": "Equestrian statue of James B. McPherson", "text_new": "{{Infobox artwork\n| image_file         = McPherson Square statue.jpg\n| italic title       = no\n| painting_alignment = Proper Left\n| image_upright      = 1\n| title              = Major General James B. McPherson\n| alt                = \n| other_language_1   =\n| other_title_1      =\n| other_language_2   =\n| other_title_2      = Brigadier General James B. McPherson\n| artist             = Louis Rebisso\n| year               = {{Start date|1876}}\n| type               = Bronze\n| height_metric             = \n| width_metric              = \n| length_metric             = \n| height_imperial        = 168\n| width_imperial         = \n| length_imperial        = 144\n| diameter__metric        = \n| diameter_imperial      = \n| imperial_unit = in\n| metric_unit = cm\n| city               = Washington, D.C.\n| owner              = National Park Service\n{{Infobox NRHP \n  | embed = yes\n  | nrhp_type            = cp | nocat = yes\n  | partof               = [[Civil War Monuments in Washington, DC]].\n  | partof_refnum        = \n  | address = \n  | location = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n  | coordinates  = {{coord|38|54|6.9|N|77|2|3.3|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = United States Washington, D.C.\n  | added = September 20, 1978 <ref name=inventory>{{cite web|url=http://nrhp.focus.nps.gov/natregsearchresult.do?fullresult=true&recordid=7| title = Civil War Monuments in Washington, DC| date = September 20, 1978 | publisher =National Park Service | accessdate = August 10, 2011 }}</ref>\n  | governing_body = [[National Park Service]]\n  | refnum = 78000257<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Major General James B. McPherson''''' is a public artwork by [[United States|American]] artist [[Louis Rebisso]], located at [[McPherson Square]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], [[United States]]. ''Major General James B. McPherson'' was originally surveyed as part of the [[Smithsonian Institution|Smithsonian's]] [[Save Outdoor Sculpture!]] survey in 1993. The monument is a [[bronze]] [[equestrian statue]] of [[American Civil War|Civil War]] hero [[James B. McPherson]].\nThe statue is a contributing monument to the [[Civil War Monuments in Washington, DC]], of the [[National Register of Historic Places]].\n\n==Description==\n\nThe memorial shows General McPherson sitting upon a horse, turned slightly to the proper right as if surveying a battlefield. He is holding the horses reins in his proper left hand and a pair of field glasses in his proper right hand. His horse, caught in mid-stride, walks with its proper right foot raised and its head turned down. The statue sits upon a rectangular [[granite]] base (H. {{convert|12|ft|0|abbr=on}}., D. {{convert|6|ft|0|abbr=on}}.). The base is adorned with a ring of small [[wreaths]] around the top and a ring of [[star]]s around the bottom, along with a ring of cannonballs.\n\nThe west side of the base is inscribed with:\n<center>\nMAJ. GEN. JAMES B. McPHERSON<br />\nATLANTA<br />\nJULY 22, 1864</center>\n\nThe east side of the base is inscribed with:\n\nERECTED BY HIS COMRADES<br />\nOF THE SOCIETY OF<br />\nTHE ARMY OF THE TENNESSEE<ref name=\"SOS\">{{cite web | author=Save Outdoor Sculptures! | year=1993 | title=Major General James B. McPherson, (sculpture)  | work=SOS! | publisher=Smithsonian | url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!siartinventories&uri=full=3100001~!325359~!0#focus | accessdate= 25 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Information==\n\n[[Confederate States Army|Confederate]] [[cannon]]s that were captured at the [[Battle of Atlanta]] were used in the casting of the piece. The base was designed by [[Smithmeyer & Pelz]] and [[Westham Granite Works]] provided the stone work.\n\nThe sculpture was authorized by the [[United States Congress]] on March 3, 1875, and was paid for by the [[Army of the Tennessee|Society of the Army of the Tennessee]]. '''Major General James B. McPherson''' was installed in Scott Square (now McPherson Square) on October 18, 1876, on the 11th annual reunion of the Army of the Tennessee.<ref name=\"SOS\"/>\n\n==Artist==\n{{Main article|Louis Rebisso}}\n\n==Condition==\n\nThis sculpture was surveyed in June 1993 for its condition and was decided that it was \"well maintained.\"<ref name=\"SOS\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of public art in Washington, D.C., Ward 2]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.hmdb.org/marker.asp?marker=17534 ''Major General James B. McPherson'' on The Historical Marker Database].\n*[http://dcmemorials.com/index_indiv0001682.htm The statue on dcMemorials.com]\n\n{{Public art in Washington, D.C.|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:1876 sculptures]]\n[[Category:Bronze sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Civil War Monuments in Washington, D.C.|McPherson]]\n[[Category:Equestrian statues in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Historic district contributing properties in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Northwest (Washington, D.C.)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artwork\n| image_file         = McPherson Square statue.jpg\n| italic title       = no\n| painting_alignment = Proper Left\n| image_size         = 300px\n| title              = Major General James B. McPherson\n| alt                = \n| other_language_1   =\n| other_title_1      =\n| other_language_2   =\n| other_title_2      = Brigadier General James B. McPherson\n| artist             = Louis Rebisso\n| year               = {{Start date|1876}}\n| type               = Bronze\n| height_metric             = \n| width_metric              = \n| length_metric             = \n| height_imperial        = 168\n| width_imperial         = \n| length_imperial        = 144\n| diameter__metric        = \n| diameter_imperial      = \n| imperial_unit = in\n| metric_unit = cm\n| city               = Washington, D.C.\n| owner              = National Park Service\n{{Infobox NRHP \n  | embed = yes\n  | nrhp_type            = cp | nocat = yes\n  | partof               = [[Civil War Monuments in Washington, DC]].\n  | partof_refnum        = \n  | address = \n  | location = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n  | coordinates  = {{coord|38|54|6.9|N|77|2|3.3|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = United States Washington, D.C.\n  | added = September 20, 1978 <ref name=inventory>{{cite web|url=http://nrhp.focus.nps.gov/natregsearchresult.do?fullresult=true&recordid=7| title = Civil War Monuments in Washington, DC| date = September 20, 1978 | publisher =National Park Service | accessdate = August 10, 2011 }}</ref>\n  | governing_body = [[National Park Service]]\n  | refnum = 78000257<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Major General James B. McPherson''''' is a public artwork by [[United States|American]] artist [[Louis Rebisso]], located at [[McPherson Square]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], [[United States]]. ''Major General James B. McPherson'' was originally surveyed as part of the [[Smithsonian Institution|Smithsonian's]] [[Save Outdoor Sculpture!]] survey in 1993. The monument is a [[bronze]] [[equestrian statue]] of [[American Civil War|Civil War]] hero [[James B. McPherson]].\nThe statue is a contributing monument to the [[Civil War Monuments in Washington, DC]], of the [[National Register of Historic Places]].\n\n==Description==\n\nThe memorial shows General McPherson sitting upon a horse, turned slightly to the proper right as if surveying a battlefield. He is holding the horses reins in his proper left hand and a pair of field glasses in his proper right hand. His horse, caught in mid-stride, walks with its proper right foot raised and its head turned down. The statue sits upon a rectangular [[granite]] base (H. {{convert|12|ft|0|abbr=on}}., D. {{convert|6|ft|0|abbr=on}}.). The base is adorned with a ring of small [[wreaths]] around the top and a ring of [[star]]s around the bottom, along with a ring of cannonballs.\n\nThe west side of the base is inscribed with:\n<center>\nMAJ. GEN. JAMES B. McPHERSON<br />\nATLANTA<br />\nJULY 22, 1864</center>\n\nThe east side of the base is inscribed with:\n\nERECTED BY HIS COMRADES<br />\nOF THE SOCIETY OF<br />\nTHE ARMY OF THE TENNESSEE<ref name=\"SOS\">{{cite web | author=Save Outdoor Sculptures! | year=1993 | title=Major General James B. McPherson, (sculpture)  | work=SOS! | publisher=Smithsonian | url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!siartinventories&uri=full=3100001~!325359~!0#focus | accessdate= 25 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Information==\n\n[[Confederate States Army|Confederate]] [[cannon]]s that were captured at the [[Battle of Atlanta]] were used in the casting of the piece. The base was designed by [[Smithmeyer & Pelz]] and [[Westham Granite Works]] provided the stone work.\n\nThe sculpture was authorized by the [[United States Congress]] on March 3, 1875, and was paid for by the [[Army of the Tennessee|Society of the Army of the Tennessee]]. '''Major General James B. McPherson''' was installed in Scott Square (now McPherson Square) on October 18, 1876, on the 11th annual reunion of the Army of the Tennessee.<ref name=\"SOS\"/>\n\n==Artist==\n{{Main article|Louis Rebisso}}\n\n==Condition==\n\nThis sculpture was surveyed in June 1993 for its condition and was decided that it was \"well maintained.\"<ref name=\"SOS\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of public art in Washington, D.C., Ward 2]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|General James B. McPherson by Louis Rebisso|''General James B. McPherson'' by Louis Rebisso}}\n*[http://www.hmdb.org/marker.asp?marker=17534 ''Major General James B. McPherson'' on The Historical Marker Database].\n*[http://dcmemorials.com/index_indiv0001682.htm The statue on dcMemorials.com]\n\n[[Category:1876 sculptures]]\n[[Category:Bronze sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Civil War Monuments in Washington, D.C.|McPherson]]\n[[Category:Equestrian statues in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Historic district contributing properties in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Northwest (Washington, D.C.)]]\n", "name_user": "Ham II", "label": "safe", "comment": "+Template:Public art in Washington, D.C.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equestrian_statue_of_James_B._McPherson"}
{"title_page": "Ingrid Lacey", "text_new": "'''Ingrid Marcella Lacey''' (born 6 November 1958) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[actress]]. She is known for her role as Julia in Series 2 of ''[[London's Burning (TV series)|London's Burning]]'', Helen Cooper in the [[Channel 4]] sitcom ''[[Drop the Dead Donkey]]'' (1993\u201398). Her film appearances include ''[[Funny Man (film)|Funny Man]]'' (1994), ''[[In Love and War (1996 film)|In Love and War]]'' (1996) and ''[[The Cat's Meow]]'' (2001).\n\n==Career==\nLacey is best known for her role as Helen Cooper in ''[[Drop the Dead Donkey]]''. She was born in [[Surrey]] and educated at [[Godalming College]] and trained at the [[Bristol Old Vic Theatre School]], graduating in 1981. She has acted in films, radio, TV series and theatre productions, such as Lolly Susi's ''Gone to LA'' at the [[Hampstead Theatre]], London, where she had to shave her head for her role of a woman suffering from [[breast cancer]] <ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/reviews/story/0,3604,231866,00.html Cancer's visible scar], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 23 February 2000</ref> and in ''The Knight of the Burning Pestle''.<ref>[http://www.thestage.co.uk/reviews/review.php/9746/the-knight-of-the-burning-pestle The Knight of the Burning Pestle], ''[[The Stage]]'', 21 September 2005</ref> She has also appeared at the [[Royal Court Theatre]] in the productions \"Blood\" and \"Our Late Night\". In 2007 she was in the [[Bush Theatre]]'s production of \"Elling\" which transferred to the [[Trafalgar Studios]], while in 2011, she appeared as Tricia in [[Brad Fraser]]'s 5 @ 50, at the [[Royal Exchange Theatre]], [[Manchester]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2011/apr/19/5-at-50-review 5 @ 50 \u2013 review], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 19 April 2011</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''[[The Cat's Meow]]'' (2001) as Jessica Barham\n* ''In Love and War'' (1996) as Elsie 'Mac' MacDonald\n* ''[[Funny Man (film)|Funny Man]]'' (1994) as Tina Taylor (UK title: Funnyman)\n\n==Theatre==\n* ''Desdemona: A Play About A Handkerchief'' (2014) - Emilia (Park Theatre, London)\n* ''The Astronaut's Chair'' (2012) - Renee (Drum Theatre, Plymouth)\n* ''5 @ 50'' (2011) - Tricia (Royal Enchange Theatre, Manchester)\n* ''[[Elling (play)|Elling]]'' - (2007) ( [[Bush Theatre]], Trafalgar Studios ), London\n* ''Knight of the Burning Pestle'' (2005) - Citizen's Wife (Young Vic, London; [[Mercury Theatre, Colchester]])\n* ''Blood'' (2003) - Madeleine (Royal Court Theatre, London)\n* ''Gone To LA'' (2000) - Ella (Hampstead Theatre, London)\n* ''Our Late Night'' (1999) - Kristin (Royal Court Theatre, London)\n* ''After the Rain'' - (Gate Theatre, Dublin, Ireland)\n* ''The Killing Of Sister George''\n* ''Charley's Aunt''\n* ''The Comedy Of Errors''\n* ''The Lion, The Witch And The Wardrobe'' as The Witch\n* ''The History Of Mr Polly''\n* ''The Resistible Rise Of Arturo Ui''\n* ''The Country Wife''\n* ''Widowers' Houses'' (1981) (Bristol Old Vic)\n* ''The Railway Children'' (Oldham Coliseum)\n\n==Television filmography==\n* ''[[New Tricks]]'' (2013) as Jane Harlow\n* ''[[Skins (UK TV series)|Skins]]'' (2011) as Catherine Creevey\n* ''[[Tracy Beaker Returns]]'' - Moving On (episode 13) (2010) as the Editor\n* ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]''\n** Animals (2005) as Helen Wilder\n** Free Fall (1999) as Chrissie Holman\n* ''[[The Last Detective]]'' - episode #1.1 (2003) TV Episode as Roxanne Palmer\n* ''[[Heartbeat (UK TV series)|Heartbeat]]'' - Honor Among Thieves (1999) as Honor Gale\n* ''Getting Hurt'' (1998) (TV) as Helen Cross\n* ''[[Pie in the Sky (TV series)|Pie in the Sky]]'' - Game Pie (1996) TV episode as Cynthia Hoskins\n* ''[[The Bill]]'' - Ties That Bind (1995) as Jane Grant\n* ''Look at the State We're In!'' (1995) (mini) TV series as Sally\n* ''Master of the Moor'' (1994) (TV)\n* ''[[The Chief (UK TV series)]]'' (1994) (TV) As Alison Dell\n* ''[[Drop the Dead Donkey]]'' (1990) as Helen Cooper (1993\u20131998)\n* ''A Woman's Guide to Adultery'' (1993) 