on|date=5 November 1999|accessdate=22 November 2017|via=www.nytimes.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171213161204/http://www.nytimes.com/1999/11/05/business/warner-lambert-gets-pfizer-offer-for-82.4-billion.html|archive-date=13 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 16\n| 1999\n| {{flagicon|GER}} [[Deutsche Telekom]]\n| {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Telecom Italia]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|81.0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|81|1999}}\n| [[Olivetti]] was able to sway key shareholders and win control of 51% of shares, killing the proposed merger of the telecommunication giants.<ref>https://www.wired.com/1999/05/deutsche-telekom-gets-dumped/</ref><ref>http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/348931.stm</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 17\n| 2014\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[21st Century Fox]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Time Warner]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|80.0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|80|2014}}\n| 21st Century Fox abandoned its takeover Time Warner Inc., due to the unwillingness of the Time Warner Board to engage with the Fox Executives. This also caused a sharp dip in Fox's stock price which made a deal unattractive to Fox shareholders.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/fox-withdraws-time-warner-bid-1407269617|title=Fox Withdraws Time Warner Bid|first1=Martin|last1=Peers|first2=Keach|last2=Hagey|date=5 August 2014|via=www.wsj.com|access-date=4 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170717131011/https://www.wsj.com/articles/fox-withdraws-time-warner-bid-1407269617|archive-date=17 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2014/07/16/time-warner-rejected-80b-offer-from-21st-century-fox-sources.html|title=Time Warner rejects $80B offer from 21st Century Fox|first=Andrew Ross|last=Sorkin|date=16 July 2014|access-date=9 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171111094251/https://www.cnbc.com/2014/07/16/time-war