rejected the deal as it planned to break up the conglomerate which the company\u2019s chairman [[Patrick Sheehy]] described as \u201cmost disadvantageous to the company, its shareholders, customers, policyholders and employees.\u201d<ref>https://apnews.com/f1f3500b28b47db7883e6adead6633ab</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 88\n| 2017\n| {{flagicon|SUI}} [[Clariant]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Huntsman Corporation|Huntsman]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|20.0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|20|2017}}\n| After months of pressure from activist investors, the companies announced they would abandon their merger plans, with investors citing a reduction in shareholder value as the cause.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-clariant-huntsman-statement/activist-investors-scupper-20-billion-clariant-huntsman-merger-idUKKBN1CW0RI|title=Activist investors scupper $20 billion Clariant-Huntsman merger|first=John Miller and Oliver|last=Hirt|website=reuters.com|accessdate=22 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171119012937/https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-clariant-huntsman-statement/activist-investors-scupper-20-billion-clariant-huntsman-merger-idUKKBN1CW0RI|archive-date=19 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of largest companies by revenue]]\n* [[List of largest employers]]\n* [[List of companies by profit and loss]]\n* [[List of public corporations by market capitalization]]\n* [[List of largest pharmaceutical mergers and acquisitions]]\n* [[List of largest corporate spin-offs]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=N|2}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Corporate finance and investment banking|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of corporate acquisitions|Largest mergers and acquisitions]]\n[[Category:Mergers and acquisitions|.]]\n[[Category:Corporation-related lists|Largest mergers and acquisitions]]\n[[Category:Economy-related lists of superlatives|Mergers and acquisitions]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Redirect|Megamerger|distributed algorithm in computing|Mega-Merger}}\n\nThe following tables list the largest [[mergers and acquisitions]] in each decade. Transaction values are given in the [[US dollar]] value for the year of the merger, adjusted for inflation. {{As of|2020|3|df=}} the largest ever acquisition was the 1999 takeover of [[Mannesmann]] by [[Vodafone Airtouch PLC]] at $183 billion (${{inflation|US|183|1999}} billion adjusted for inflation). [[Pfizer]] appears in these lists the most times with three entries, for a combined transaction value of $218 billion. Mergers and acquisitions are notated with the year the transaction was initiated, not necessarily completed. Mergers are shown as the market value of the combined entities.\n\n==Free market enterprises==\n\n===1870s===\nTop M&A deals worldwide by value from 1870 to 1879:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n!Rank\n!Year\n!Purchaser\n!Purchased\n!Transaction value<br/><small>(in billions USD)</small>\n!<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.usinflationcalculator.com/|title=US Inflation Calculator|website=US Inflation Calculator|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131028120632/http://www.usinflationcalculator.com/|archive-date=2013-10-28|url-status=live}}</ref> Inflation adjusted<br/><small>(in billions 2019 USD)</small>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|1879\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Pacific Coast Oil Company]]<ref>https://books.google.com/books?id=2CHLmPx2PJ0C&pg=PA61#v=onepage&q&f=false</ref>\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Star Oil]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|0.001\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|0.024\n|}\n\n===1900s===\nTop M&A deals worldwide by value from 1900 to 1909:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n!Rank\n!Year\n!Purchaser\n!Purchased\n!Transaction value<br/><small>(in billions USD)</small>\n!<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Inflation adjusted<br/><small>(in billions 2019 USD)</small>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|1901\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[United States Steel Corporation]]<ref>http://www.fundinguniverse.com/company-histories/united-states-steel-corporation-history/</ref>\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Carnegie Steel Company]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|0.492\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|0.492|1901}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|1900\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Standard Oil]]<ref>https://books.google.com/books?id=bBvz_YxlB-AC&pg=PA128#v=onepage&q&f=false</ref>\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Pacific Coast Oil Company]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|0.001\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|0.026\n|}\n\n===1940s===\nTop M&A deals worldwide by value from 1940 to 1949:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n!Rank\n!Year\n!Purchaser\n!Purchased\n!Transaction value<br/><small>(in billions USD)</small>\n!<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Inflation adjusted<br/><small>(in billions 2019 USD)</small>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|1948\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Burlington Mills]]<ref name=\"ftc.gov\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ftc.gov/system/files/documents/reports/statistical-report-mergers-acquisitions-1978/statistical_report_on_mergers_aug1980.pdf |title=Report on mergers |website=www.ftc.gov |access-date=2017-11-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517161956/https://www.ftc.gov/system/files/documents/reports/statistical-report-mergers-acquisitions-1978/statistical_report_on_mergers_aug1980.pdf |archive-date=2017-05-17 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[May McEwen Kaiser]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|0.014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|0.140\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|1947\n|{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Zinc Corporation]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article43762688|title=METAL MERGER PLANNED Zinc Corp. Offer To Imperial Smelting|date=9 April 1948|publisher=|page=4|via=Trove}}</ref>\n|{{flagicon|GBR}} [[Smelting Corporation]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"