king [[BASF]]. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chemanager-online.com/en/news-opinions/headlines/chemchina-and-sinochem-merge-2018|title=ChemChina and SinoChem to Merge in 2018 - chemanager-online.com - Chemistry and Life Science|first=Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co.|last=KGaA|website=www.chemanager-online.com|accessdate=22 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201033411/http://www.chemanager-online.com/en/news-opinions/headlines/chemchina-and-sinochem-merge-2018|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cityam.com/264312/chinese-firms-chemchina-and-sinochem-said-talks-over-mega|title=Chinese firms said to be in mega-merger talks. But do they have chemistry?|first=William|last=Turvill|date=8 May 2017|website=cityam.com|accessdate=22 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201042029/http://www.cityam.com/264312/chinese-firms-chemchina-and-sinochem-said-talks-over-mega|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afr.com/business/manufacturing/tieup-between-sinochem-and-chemchina-in-a-class-of-its-own-20170510-gw1gf2#|title=Tie-up between Sinochem and ChemChina in a class of its own|date=10 May 2017|website=afr.com|accessdate=22 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201042048/http://www.afr.com/business/manufacturing/tieup-between-sinochem-and-chemchina-in-a-class-of-its-own-20170510-gw1gf2|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atimes.com/article/chemchina-sinochem-merger-create-worlds-largest-chem-group/|title=ChemChina-Sinochem merger to create world's largest chem group|website=atimes.com|accessdate=22 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180119163742/http://www.atimes.com/article/chemchina-sinochem-merger-create-worlds-largest-chem-group/|archive-date=19 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In January 2020 ChemChina and Sinochem consolidated their agricultural assets into a new holding company, to be called Syngenta Group.<ref>https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-chemchina-sinochem-syngenta/chemchina-sinochem-merge-agricultural-assets-syngenta-idUKKBN1Z40HB</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 5\n| 2015\n| {{flagicon|CHN}} [[China Power Investment]]\n| {{flagicon|CHN}} [[State Nuclear Power Technology]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|112.6\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|112.6|2015}}\n| In June 2015 the Chinese cabinet approved plans to merge state owned China Power Investment (CPIC) with State Nuclear Power Technology increasing the exports of nuclear technology from the country, creating the new entity [[China Power New Energy Development Company Limited]], with assets of more than $112.6 billion) and annual revenues of more than $32.6 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.power-technology.com/news/newschina-announces-merger-of-state-nuclear-power-technology-and-the-china-power-investment-4590782|title=China announces merger of State Nuclear Power Technology and the China Power Investment - Power Technology|date=1 June 2015|website=power-technology.com|accessdate=22 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831001232/http://www.power-technology.com/news/newschina-announces-merger-of-state-nuclear-power-technology-and-the-china-power-investment-4590782|archive-date=31 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/C-Chinese-nuclear-giant-officially-launched-1607155.html|title=Chinese nuclear giant officially launched|website=www.world-nuclear-news.org|accessdate=22 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170701010744/http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/C-Chinese-nuclear-giant-officially-launched-1607155.html|archive-date=1 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 6\n| 2018\n| {{flagicon|CHN}} [[China National Nuclear Corp]]\n| {{flagicon|CHN}} [[China Nuclear Engineering & Construction ]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|99.0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|99|2018}}\n|Merger of China\u2019s second largest nuclear power producer, and their top nuclear power plant builder.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/us-china-power-nuclear/china-goes-nuclear-with-latest-state-brokered-power-deal-idUKKBN1FK0S4|title=China goes nuclear with latest state-brokered power deal|first=Josephine|last=Mason|access-date=2018-01-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180131190345/https://uk.reuters.com/article/us-china-power-nuclear/china-goes-nuclear-with-latest-state-brokered-power-deal-idUKKBN1FK0S4|archive-date=2018-01-31|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Largest ever deals which have failed to complete==\nThis lists catalogues M&A (above or equal to $20 billion in transaction value) deals which were confirmed, but for a number of reasons, failed to complete.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n!Rank\n!Year\n!Purchaser\n!Purchased\n!Transaction value<br/><small>{{nowrap|(in billions USD)}}</small>\n!Inflation adjusted value\n!Note\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1\n| 2019\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Altria]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Philip Morris International]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|200.0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|200|2019}}\n|The merger was called off after a chilly reaction from investors, vaping related illnesses, and Altria's increasingly scrutinized $12.8 billion investment in vaping leader [[JUUL]].<ref>https://www.cnbc.com/2019/09/25/philip-morris-and-altria-end-merger-talks.html</ref> \n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2\n| 2015\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Pfizer]]\n| {{flagicon|IRL}}{{flagicon|USA}} [[Allergan, plc]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|160.0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|160|2015}}\n|The deal fell through over changes made to [[tax inversion]] legislation by the [[US Government]].<ref name=\"wolfstreet.com\">{{cite web|url=http://wolfstreet.com/2016/04/07/end-of-boom-failed-us-mergers-acquisitions-2016-all-time-record/|title=M&A Boom Implodes, US Deal Failures in 2016 Worst Ever|date=7 April 2016|access-date=22 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923041913/http://wolfstreet.com/2016/04/07/end-of-boom-failed-us-mergers-acquisitions-2016-all-time-record/|archive-date=23 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> \n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 3\n| 2008\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} {{flagicon|AUS}} [[BHP Billiton]]\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Rio Tinto Group|Rio Tinto]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|148.0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|148|2008}}\n| As commodity prices fell in value, the deal became too risky for BHP Billiton to complete.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB122759796497756137|title=Death of a Megadeal: BHP Ends Its Pursuit of Rio|first1=Robert Guy|last1=Matthews|first2=Dana|last2=Cimilluca|first3=Patrick|last3=Barta|date=26 November 2008|via=Wall Street Journal|access-date=18 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170219012251/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB122759796497756137|archive-date=19 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"wolfstreet.com\"/>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 4\n| 2017\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Kraft Heinz]]\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} {{flagicon|NED}} [[Unilever| Unilever plc]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|143.0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|143|2017}}\n| Kraft's offer was an 18% premium to Unilever's closing share price the day before the announcement, however Unilever Executives claimed the deal undervalued the company.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-39006302|title=Marmite owner Unilever sees no merit in Kraft takeover|date=17 February 2017|via=www.bbc.co.uk|access-date=21 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730021338/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-39006302|archive-date=30 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> as well as job-cut implications and regulator approval issues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.investegate.co.uk/unilever-plc--ulvr-/rns/statement-re-announcement-by-kraft-heinz-company/201702171315072133X/|title=FE Investegate -Unilever PLC Announcements - Unilever PLC: Statement re announcement by Kraft Heinz Company|access-date=2017-02-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170219030914/http://www.investegate.co.uk/unilever-plc--ulvr-/rns/statement-re-announcement-by-kraft-heinz-company/201702171315072133X/|archive-date=2017-02-19|url-status=live}}</ref> The bid was formally dropped on February 19, citing the complexities of acquiring control in a Dutch entity without the support of shareholders.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-39022692|title=Kraft Heinz drops Unilever takeover bid|first=Howard|last=Mustoe|date=20 February 2017|via=www.bbc.co.uk|access-date=21 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919060637/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-39022692|archive-date=19 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 5\n| 1999\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[MCI WorldCom]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Sprint Nextel|Sprint]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|129.0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|129|1999}}\n| The US [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]] and [[European Commission]] prohibited the merger on competition grounds, with the DoJ filing a lawsuit against the transaction.<ref name=\"wolfstreet.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-00-668_en.htm|title=European Commission - PRESS RELEASES - Press release - Commission prohibits merger between MCI WorldCom and Sprint|access-date=2016-09-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923035417/http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-00-668_en.htm|archive-date=2016-09-23|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/uk/news/doj-files-to-block-worldcom-sprint-merger/|title=DOJ files to block WorldCom-Sprint merger|access-date=2017-02-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170219031128/https://www.cnet.com/uk/news/doj-files-to-block-worldcom-sprint-merger/|archive-date=2017-02-19|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>https://www.cnet.com/news/mci-worldcom-buys-sprint-for-129-billion/</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 6\n| 2014\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Pfizer]]\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} {{flagicon|SWE}} [[Astra Zeneca]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|123.0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|123|2014}}\n|Significant concerns were raised by the [[UK Government]] over job security, in the end leading to a deal being abandoned due to resistance from the AstraZeneca Board.<ref name=\"wolfstreet.com\"/>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 7\n| 2018\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Broadcom Ltd]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Qualcomm Inc]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|121.0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|121|2018}}\n| Qualcomm claimed that Broadcom had undervalued the business but did propose to meet Broadcom officials, with the initial offer of $121 billion ($140 billion with debt).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-43401675|title=Trump pressure scuppers $140bn tech deal|date=14 March 2018|via=www.bbc.co.uk|access-date=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014164924/https://www.bbc.com/news/business-43401675|archive-date=14 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/us-qualcomm-m-a-broadcom/qualcomm-rejects-broadcoms-revised-buyout-offer-proposes-meeting-idUKKBN1FS391|title=Qualcomm warns of customer losses, legal hazards to Broadcom buyout|first=Sonam|last=Rai|access-date=2018-02-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180210001643/https://uk.reuters.com/article/us-qualcomm-m-a-broadcom/qualcomm-rejects-broadcoms-revised-buyout-offer-proposes-meeting-idUKKBN1FS391|archive-date=2018-02-10|url-status=live}}</ref> On February 21, Broadcom reduced their offer to $117 billion in ligh