e=\"text-align:center;\"|24.0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|24|1998}}\n| Bank of New York called off its takeover proposal after Mellon\u2019s board declined to meet with Bank of New York officials to discuss the merger. The two would later merge in 2007.<ref>https://money.cnn.com/1998/05/20/deals/mellon//</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 81\n| 2018\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Albertsons]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Rite Aid]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|24.0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|24|2018}}\n| Albertsons and Rite Aid called off the planned merger after several advisory firms recommended voting against the proposal.<ref>https://www.cnbc.com/2018/02/20/albertsons-to-acquire-rite-aid-in-defense-move-against-amazon.html</ref><ref>https://www.supermarketnews.com/retail-financial/albertsons-rite-aid-kill-merger-deal</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 82\n| 2006\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Johnson & Johnson]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Guidant]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|23.2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|23.2|2006}}\n| After the re-negotiated lower price of $21.5 billion was trumped by Boston Scientifics offer of $24.6 billion, Johnson & Johnson raised their offer to  $23.2 billion.<ref>https://money.cnn.com/2006/01/25/news/companies/guidant_jnj/index.htm</ref><ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/12/business/johnson-raises-bid-for-control-of-guidant.html</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 83\n| 2016\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Mondelez International]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[The Hershey Company]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|23.0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|23|2016}}\n| Mondelez ceased its pursuit of the Hershey Co acquisition after the chocolate company turned down its $23 billion cash-and-stock offer.<ref>https://www.reuters.com/article/us-hershey-m-a-mondelez-intl-idUSKCN1142BE</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 84\n| 1995\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Tracinda]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Chrysler]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|22.8\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|22.8|1995}}\n| Tracinda led by [[Kirk Kerkorian]] was unable to come up with the financing in order to complete the deal. Chrysler was able to leverage its relationships with investment banks to block Kerkorian from being able to get the money necessary for the takeover.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1995/06/01/kerkorian-withdraws-bid-to-acquire-chrysler-corp/a511c4bd-c437-43a0-a2e8-24a57095f2de/</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 85\n| 1996\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[British Telecom]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[MCI Inc.]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|22.0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|22|1996}}\n| British Telecom held a partial stake in MCI since 1994 and was looking to acquire the entirety of it. [[Worldcom]] ended up winning the takeover fight with a $37 billion bid..<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/1996/11/02/business/a-british-company-weighs-buying-mci-in-22-billion-deal.html</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 86\n| 2020\n| {{flagicon|JPN}} [[Seven & i Holdings]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Marathon Petroleum]] <small>([[Speedway LLC]])</small>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|22.0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|22|2020}}\n| Seven & i walked away from the potential deal, citing concerns over the price.<ref>https://uk.reuters.com/article/us-speedway-m-a-seven-i-hldgs/japans-seven-i-abandons-22-billion-bid-for-speedway-gas-stations-in-u-s-source-idUKKBN20S11A</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 87\n| 1989\n| {{flagicon|FRA}}{{flagicon|GBR}} [[Sir James Goldsmith]] <br/> {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Jacob Rothschild, 4th Baron Rothschild]] <br/> {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Kerry Packer]]\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[British American Tobacco]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|21.0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{inflation|US|21|1989}}\n| British American Tobacco rejected the deal as it planned to break up the conglomerate which the com